00:02:54.230 --> 00:02:59.130
GILBERT: Everybody
wants happiness.

00:02:59.130 --> 00:03:04.200
Its a universal human desire.

00:03:04.200 --> 00:03:10.330
But it's a desire
not easily satisfied.

00:03:10.330 --> 00:03:13.560
"We search without finding
it, and when we do find it,"

00:03:13.560 --> 00:03:16.060
it doesn't seem
to last very long.

00:03:16.060 --> 00:03:18.600
WOMAN: Why is it

00:03:18.600 --> 00:03:21.830
that it is so difficult for
us to hold onto contentment?

00:03:21.830 --> 00:03:24.560
"And why are we so fleeting,
and why are we so fickle?"

00:03:24.560 --> 00:03:27.160
"Why is it that one day the
things that make us happy,"

00:03:27.160 --> 00:03:29.130
the next day bring us misery?

00:03:29.130 --> 00:03:31.430
"MAN: Happiness, get over
yourself, what happiness?"

00:03:31.430 --> 00:03:34.060
"You know, life is going
to be always challenging."

00:03:34.060 --> 00:03:36.260
"It's always going to be
a pain, so get over it."

00:03:36.260 --> 00:03:37.830
MAN: I don't think it's
that much of a mystery.

00:03:37.830 --> 00:03:39.460
"If you dont have a
job that you like,"

00:03:39.460 --> 00:03:44.000
"and youre not having sex,
you're just not gonna be happy."

00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:47.560
"I think happiness is
a temporary state,"

00:03:47.560 --> 00:04:00.800
but its a juicy one. (laughs)

00:04:00.800 --> 00:04:02.160
GILBERT: I'm Dan Gilbert.

00:04:02.160 --> 00:04:03.500
Im a social psychologist

00:04:03.500 --> 00:04:06.130
and a professor here
at Harvard University.

00:04:06.130 --> 00:04:08.400
"For centuries, happiness
has been a subject"

00:04:08.400 --> 00:04:09.900
for poets and philosophers.

00:04:09.900 --> 00:04:13.630
"But in the last few decades,
psychologists, neuroscientists,"

00:04:13.630 --> 00:04:16.260
even economists have
begun to study happiness

00:04:16.260 --> 00:04:18.830
using the same scientific
methods they use to study

00:04:18.830 --> 00:04:27.130
every other aspect
of human behavior.

00:04:27.130 --> 00:04:29.160
"Of course, scientists have
only recently gotten into"

00:04:29.160 --> 00:04:31.700
"the happiness business, but
that business has been booming"

00:04:31.700 --> 00:04:34.830
for a long time.

00:04:34.830 --> 00:04:37.500
You have to train your mind to
recall the simple successes...

00:04:37.500 --> 00:04:40.560
"GILBERT: Turn on
the television, surf the
Web, visit a bookstore,"

00:04:40.560 --> 00:04:42.560
and youll see that theres
no shortage of people

00:04:42.560 --> 00:04:46.460
offering advice about happiness.

00:04:46.460 --> 00:04:47.600
"Its going to be fun, yall!"

00:04:47.600 --> 00:04:49.700
"All my needs, desires..."

00:04:49.700 --> 00:04:52.160
GILBERT: Theyre all part of
a large and growing business

00:04:52.160 --> 00:04:57.100
known as the self-help industry.

00:04:57.100 --> 00:05:00.160
"This industry may or may
not have made anyone happy,"

00:05:00.160 --> 00:05:03.000
but it's definitely made
some people very rich.

00:05:03.000 --> 00:05:06.460
WOMAN: It is my pleasure
to welcome you here today

00:05:06.460 --> 00:05:08.230
"to the ""You Control
Your Life"" conference."

00:05:08.230 --> 00:05:11.960
"GILBERT: Last year, Americans
spent about $10 billion"

00:05:11.960 --> 00:05:13.730
on self-help.

00:05:13.730 --> 00:05:15.860
Youre in the preferred section.

00:05:15.860 --> 00:05:18.960
"GILBERT: Much of that
money was brought in by
conferences like this one,"

00:05:18.960 --> 00:05:23.460
"run by Hay House, a leading
self-help publisher."

00:05:23.460 --> 00:05:27.160
"WOMAN: For just $20, we
can send you the CDs."

00:05:27.160 --> 00:05:29.760
GILBERT: Hay House
sells books and DVDs

00:05:29.760 --> 00:05:32.000
on everything from diet
and personal fitness

00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:34.800
"to ""Fairy Magic""
and ""Angel Therapy."""

00:05:34.800 --> 00:05:36.530
"Wow, theres a lot of
money to be spent here."

00:05:36.530 --> 00:05:38.500
"Yes, there is."

00:05:38.500 --> 00:05:40.860
How much money are you
going to spend here?

00:05:40.860 --> 00:05:43.030
"Well, we didnt even make
it around the tables,"

00:05:43.030 --> 00:05:45.230
but it looks like we're
going to be spending a lot.

00:05:45.230 --> 00:05:46.630
Stuff looks great.

00:05:46.630 --> 00:05:48.700
GILBERT: The desire
for happiness drives
different people

00:05:48.700 --> 00:05:50.330
toward different things.

00:05:50.330 --> 00:05:52.360
Some have come here
hoping to lose weight;

00:05:52.360 --> 00:05:54.330
"some are hoping to
find a new partner,"

00:05:54.330 --> 00:05:57.800
"a new career, or a whole
new view of the universe."

00:05:57.800 --> 00:06:01.430
"Unbelievingly, amazingly, about
the mind over body connection."

00:06:01.430 --> 00:06:04.730
"Getting a better job,
love, relationships..."

00:06:04.730 --> 00:06:06.400
All the good things in life.

00:06:06.400 --> 00:06:09.330
GILBERT: But some people
have come here with
very serious problems

00:06:09.330 --> 00:06:12.800
and they may not be
in the right place.

00:06:12.800 --> 00:06:17.260
"Many have been drawn by Louise
Hay, the founder of Hay House."

00:06:17.260 --> 00:06:19.800
She claims to have
cured herself of cancer

00:06:19.800 --> 00:06:22.760
"through positive thinking and
other self-help techniques,"

00:06:22.760 --> 00:06:26.330
"and she tells others
that they can do it, too."

00:06:26.330 --> 00:06:28.560
"Although her claims have never
been medically verified,"

00:06:28.560 --> 00:06:30.400
shes been a guest on Oprah

00:06:30.400 --> 00:06:35.360
"and her memoir,
Heal Your Life, has sold
over 35 million copies,"

00:06:35.360 --> 00:06:38.560
making her one of the best-
selling authors of all time.

00:06:38.560 --> 00:06:42.200
WOMAN: Please join me in
welcoming Louise Hay.

00:06:42.200 --> 00:06:55.130
(applause)

00:06:55.130 --> 00:06:59.930
I choose the thoughts
that make me feel good.

00:06:59.930 --> 00:07:04.630
"And if you will be very careful
about the thoughts you think,"

00:07:04.630 --> 00:07:06.560
that you choose to think...

00:07:06.560 --> 00:07:08.060
GILBERT: Hay is
right when she says

00:07:08.060 --> 00:07:10.060
that our thoughts
affect our feelings

00:07:10.060 --> 00:07:12.460
and that we have some control
over the thoughts we think.

00:07:12.460 --> 00:07:15.030
"HAY: Life loves
you, I love you."

00:07:15.030 --> 00:07:17.530
Do you love you?

00:07:17.530 --> 00:07:19.430
Thats the important thing.

00:07:19.430 --> 00:07:21.200
AUDIENCE MEMBER: We love you!

00:07:21.200 --> 00:07:22.630
"Thank you, thank
you, I accept."

00:07:22.630 --> 00:07:24.230
"I do, you're damn right!"

00:07:24.230 --> 00:07:27.330
(laughter)

00:07:27.330 --> 00:07:29.030
GILBERT: But Hay also believes
that thoughts are the cause

00:07:29.030 --> 00:07:30.460
of all misfortunes...

00:07:30.460 --> 00:07:33.900
"Because, remember,
somebody who has depression"

00:07:33.900 --> 00:07:37.460
is choosing thoughts that
make them feel rotten.

00:07:37.460 --> 00:07:41.030
GILBERT: That by
thinking the wrong way we
can give ourselves cancer

00:07:41.030 --> 00:07:44.330
"or AIDS or depression,
cause cars to hit us,"

00:07:44.330 --> 00:07:47.130
or make ourselves the target
of a terrorist attack.

00:07:47.130 --> 00:07:49.700
"HAY: When I became
80, I decided"

00:07:49.700 --> 00:07:52.660
"that it was going to be the
best decade of my entire life,"

00:07:52.660 --> 00:07:54.660
and it is. (applause)

00:07:54.660 --> 00:07:57.660
Im 82.

00:07:57.660 --> 00:07:59.100
"As I go through your book,"

00:07:59.100 --> 00:08:02.530
I see all sorts of maladies
and various kinds of thoughts

00:08:02.530 --> 00:08:04.560
that you say can cause them.

00:08:04.560 --> 00:08:06.860
Alzheimers is an
inability to face life;

00:08:06.860 --> 00:08:08.930
"leprosy, an inability
to handle life at all."

00:08:08.930 --> 00:08:10.660
"Oh, youre picking
the fun ones."

00:08:10.660 --> 00:08:12.400
People who have Alzheimers

00:08:12.400 --> 00:08:16.000
are really removing themselves
from life completely.

00:08:16.000 --> 00:08:17.560
How do you know?

00:08:17.560 --> 00:08:19.360
"How do you know what
you're saying is right?
Oh, my inner ding."

00:08:19.360 --> 00:08:21.400
Your ding? My inner ding.

00:08:21.400 --> 00:08:23.160
It speaks to me.

00:08:23.160 --> 00:08:26.530
"Yes, it feels right or
it doesnt feel right."

00:08:26.530 --> 00:08:29.860
Happiness is choosing thoughts
that make you feel good.

00:08:29.860 --> 00:08:31.960
Its really very simple.

00:08:31.960 --> 00:08:35.660
I hear you saying that
even if there were no proof

00:08:35.660 --> 00:08:37.400
"for what you believed,"

00:08:37.400 --> 00:08:41.230
"or even if there was
""scientific evidence""
against it..."

00:08:41.230 --> 00:08:43.260
"Well, I dont believe in
scientific evidence,"

00:08:43.260 --> 00:08:45.030
I really dont.

00:08:45.030 --> 00:08:46.430
Science is fairly new.

00:08:46.430 --> 00:08:48.760
It hasnt been around that long.

00:08:48.760 --> 00:08:50.730
"We think its such a big
deal, but its, you know,"

00:08:50.730 --> 00:08:52.530
its just a way of
looking at life.

00:08:52.530 --> 00:08:54.430
But youre telling it
to millions of people

00:08:54.430 --> 00:08:56.830
"and you're telling them
it's right for them, too."

00:08:56.830 --> 00:09:00.500
I'm telling them
what's right for me.

00:09:00.500 --> 00:09:02.760
(sighs)

00:09:02.760 --> 00:09:05.160
"My inner ding,
that's all I can say."

00:09:05.160 --> 00:09:06.600
GILBERT: You know what?

00:09:06.600 --> 00:09:08.530
Science is fairly new.

00:09:08.530 --> 00:09:11.360
But when we want to know
what causes stars to explode

00:09:11.360 --> 00:09:13.330
"or butterflies to migrate,"

00:09:13.330 --> 00:09:17.660
we rely on scientific evidence
rather than our inner ding.

00:09:17.660 --> 00:09:19.500
So why not do the
same thing to find out

00:09:19.500 --> 00:09:21.800
what causes human happiness?

00:09:21.800 --> 00:09:23.160
"MAN: For thousands of years,"

00:09:23.160 --> 00:09:25.530
philosophers were
asking about happiness

00:09:25.530 --> 00:09:29.400
and talking about happiness
but without any data.

00:09:29.400 --> 00:09:31.560
And only probably in
the last 30 or 40 years

00:09:31.560 --> 00:09:35.060
"have we actually collected
scientific data, rigorous data,"

00:09:35.060 --> 00:09:38.430
measured happiness and started
to begin to see what is it

00:09:38.430 --> 00:09:39.860
that leads to happiness.

00:09:39.860 --> 00:09:42.960
GILBERT: Psychologist
Ed Diener is a pioneer

00:09:42.960 --> 00:09:45.000
in the study of happiness.

00:09:45.000 --> 00:09:47.560
"Since 1980, he and
his collaborators"

00:09:47.560 --> 00:09:49.230
"have crossed the
globe to measure it,"

00:09:49.230 --> 00:09:52.860
"surveying diverse
communities from the
Maasai tribe in Africa,"

00:09:52.860 --> 00:09:56.730
"to the Inuit of
northern Canada,"

00:09:56.730 --> 00:09:58.800
to the Amish of
rural Pennsylvania

00:09:58.800 --> 00:10:01.400
"and many, many others."

00:10:01.400 --> 00:10:05.360
And the methods Diener uses are
as diverse as his subjects.

00:10:05.360 --> 00:10:08.700
"DIENER: In happiness
research, we ask people
how happy they are"

00:10:08.700 --> 00:10:10.260
on a one to ten scale.

00:10:10.260 --> 00:10:13.430
We also look at brain waves.

00:10:13.430 --> 00:10:15.260
You can look at hormones

00:10:15.260 --> 00:10:18.630
"like cortisol that reflects
stress, for example."

00:10:18.630 --> 00:10:20.430
You can also ask
family and friends

00:10:20.430 --> 00:10:22.200
"how happy that person is,"

00:10:22.200 --> 00:10:24.960
because family and friends see
how happy they say they are

00:10:24.960 --> 00:10:27.660
and how happy they
act in everyday lives.

00:10:27.660 --> 00:10:33.260
GILBERT: Diener has
gathered data on nearly
a quarter million people

00:10:33.260 --> 00:10:36.100
"and has found that the happy
ones have better health,"

00:10:36.100 --> 00:10:38.330
"better relationships, better
sex lives, better careers"

00:10:38.330 --> 00:10:41.730
and better just about
everything else.

00:10:41.730 --> 00:10:44.160
DIENER: We think thats
an evolutionary thing.

00:10:44.160 --> 00:10:45.660
And the people who are happy

00:10:45.660 --> 00:10:49.300
probably out-achieve the other
people and out-reproduce them

00:10:49.300 --> 00:10:51.130
and theres more
of us around now.

00:10:51.130 --> 00:10:54.900
"GILBERT: Dieners findings
have been confirmed
by psychologists,"

00:10:54.900 --> 00:10:57.560
neuroscientists and
economists around the world.

00:10:57.560 --> 00:11:00.300
We now know a great deal about

00:11:00.300 --> 00:11:02.530
"what actually
makes people happy,"

00:11:02.530 --> 00:11:06.730
and it isnt always
what we think.

00:11:06.730 --> 00:11:07.830
What does happiness mean to you?

00:11:07.830 --> 00:11:09.200
Im a firm believer

00:11:09.200 --> 00:11:10.300
in money is happiness.

00:11:10.300 --> 00:11:11.530
"Okay, I have to be honest."

00:11:11.530 --> 00:11:13.300
My children cause
I love my children.

00:11:13.300 --> 00:11:15.260
I like my summer camp the best.

00:11:15.260 --> 00:11:16.730
Is that the best?

00:11:16.730 --> 00:11:18.630
That makes you happy?

00:11:18.630 --> 00:11:20.260
What do you do to
make yourself happier?

00:11:20.260 --> 00:11:22.730
"Well, I dont mean
to be recalcitrant,"

00:11:22.730 --> 00:11:25.830
but I dont do anything
in order to be happy.

00:11:25.830 --> 00:11:28.130
Rolling down your
window and letting...

00:11:28.130 --> 00:11:30.030
"turn the music on, letting
the breeze come in."

00:11:30.030 --> 00:11:32.430
What would you say is your
greatest source of happiness?

00:11:32.430 --> 00:11:34.760
"Well, I get a great
deal of happiness"

00:11:34.760 --> 00:11:36.660
from beautiful jewelry.

00:11:36.660 --> 00:11:37.760
Jewelry? Yes.

00:11:37.760 --> 00:11:39.360
(laughter)

00:11:39.360 --> 00:11:41.260
GILBERT: There are a lot
of different opinions
about what causes

00:11:41.260 --> 00:11:43.800
"happiness, but
research suggests"

00:11:43.800 --> 00:11:46.960
that not all of them
are exactly on target.

00:11:46.960 --> 00:11:49.330
Do you think marriage is
a source of happiness?

00:11:49.330 --> 00:11:51.060
BOTH: Most of the time.

00:11:51.060 --> 00:11:54.700
Depends on what your
marriage is like.

00:11:54.700 --> 00:11:56.330
What do you think
about marriage?

00:11:56.330 --> 00:11:58.060
Do you think its a source of
happiness for most people? No.

00:11:58.060 --> 00:11:59.930
What about marriage?

00:11:59.930 --> 00:12:01.800
Do you think married people are
happier than unmarried people?

00:12:01.800 --> 00:12:03.360
No.

00:12:03.360 --> 00:12:05.660
I dont think theyre less happy;
I think it just depends.

00:12:05.660 --> 00:12:08.800
"GILBERT: Not everyone lives
happily ever after, of course,"

00:12:08.800 --> 00:12:11.100
"but studies do show
that on average,"

00:12:11.100 --> 00:12:13.000
"married people are wealthier,"

00:12:13.000 --> 00:12:17.430
"healthier and, yes,
happier than others."

00:12:17.430 --> 00:12:18.730
Do you think children
make people happy?

00:12:18.730 --> 00:12:20.530
I think so.

00:12:20.530 --> 00:12:23.160
"I mean, I think theyll be
a part of my happiness."

00:12:23.160 --> 00:12:25.060
Yes or no: do children
make you happy?

00:12:25.060 --> 00:12:26.430
Mine do.

00:12:26.430 --> 00:12:28.960
GILBERT: So what about
those bundles of joy?

00:12:28.960 --> 00:12:32.660
"Well, studies show that parents
are no happier than non-parents"

00:12:32.660 --> 00:12:34.960
and are often less happy.

00:12:34.960 --> 00:12:35.860
GILBERT: Can money
buy happiness?

00:12:35.860 --> 00:12:38.130
"No. No, it doesnt."

00:12:38.130 --> 00:12:40.530
"Do you think money can buy
happiness, can bring happiness?"

00:12:40.530 --> 00:12:42.260
No.

00:12:42.260 --> 00:12:43.530
Does money buy happiness?

00:12:43.530 --> 00:12:44.660
Not at all.

00:12:44.660 --> 00:12:45.860
What about money?

00:12:45.860 --> 00:12:47.200
Do you think money
makes people happy?

00:12:47.200 --> 00:12:48.700
Absolutely.

00:12:48.700 --> 00:12:50.100
And the more the better?

00:12:50.100 --> 00:12:54.030
"For me, especially,
the more the better."

00:12:54.030 --> 00:12:55.260
GILBERT: Guess what?

00:12:55.260 --> 00:12:56.660
Money does cause happiness.

00:12:56.660 --> 00:12:58.630
"On average, the more
money people have,"

00:12:58.630 --> 00:13:00.260
the happier they tend to be.

00:13:00.260 --> 00:13:02.060
"So, money? Yes."

00:13:02.060 --> 00:13:03.760
Marriage? Probably.

00:13:03.760 --> 00:13:06.130
Children? Not so much.

00:13:06.130 --> 00:13:08.060
What science is
teaching us about these

00:13:08.060 --> 00:13:11.600
"and many other things is that
they are related to happiness,"

00:13:11.600 --> 00:13:16.830
but not necessarily in
the way you might think.

00:13:16.830 --> 00:13:19.130
MAN: I grew up in
the South Bronx.

00:13:19.130 --> 00:13:23.930
"We had every gang banger, the
Savage Skulls and the Bloods,"

00:13:23.930 --> 00:13:25.100
and the this and the that.

00:13:25.100 --> 00:13:26.660
It was difficult to survive.

00:13:26.660 --> 00:13:30.230
And I was always one paycheck
away from being homeless.

00:13:30.230 --> 00:13:33.930
"So, for two-and-a-half
years, every week,"

00:13:33.930 --> 00:13:36.330
"regardless of what
the jackpot was,"

00:13:36.330 --> 00:13:38.660
I would go in and
just play the lottery.

00:13:38.660 --> 00:13:43.760
(chiming bell)

00:13:43.760 --> 00:13:47.060
NEWSCASTER: Falcon
won $45 million.

00:13:47.060 --> 00:13:51.030
He is New York's
single-largest winner ever.

00:13:51.030 --> 00:13:54.800
Today the former starving artist
said hell take his winnings

00:13:54.800 --> 00:13:57.860
and begin his dream performance:
a one-man show he calls

00:13:57.860 --> 00:14:00.900
"""A Short Puerto Rican Guy
Sings Songs of Angst."""

00:14:00.900 --> 00:14:03.600
"Now I can afford to rent
out a theater and do it,"

00:14:03.600 --> 00:14:05.030
and do it the way
I want to do it.

00:14:05.030 --> 00:14:06.260
Im a performance artist.

00:14:06.260 --> 00:14:07.800
Usually people are
always telling me

00:14:07.800 --> 00:14:09.430
"what it is I should be doing,
and I shouldnt be doing that,"

00:14:09.430 --> 00:14:11.400
and I should be and now I'm
just gonna do it my way.

00:14:11.400 --> 00:14:12.260
Flash

00:14:12.260 --> 00:14:13.230
Bam

00:14:13.230 --> 00:14:16.930
Wonderful you

00:14:16.930 --> 00:14:20.060
Came by.

00:14:20.060 --> 00:14:23.730
(applause)

00:14:23.730 --> 00:14:31.930
FALCON: Life is change and
money is going to change you.

00:14:31.930 --> 00:14:33.930
I moved into a
beautiful building.

00:14:33.930 --> 00:14:36.900
"An uber-luxury apartment,
in an uber-luxury building."

00:14:36.900 --> 00:14:40.560
I'm getting all the things
that I dreamt of getting.

00:14:40.560 --> 00:14:43.360
Anything Italian is
a great pleasure.

00:14:43.360 --> 00:14:44.860
(laughs)

00:14:44.860 --> 00:14:46.130
It applies to so many things:

00:14:46.130 --> 00:14:48.230
"the art, the clothing."

00:14:48.230 --> 00:14:52.030
"All the good stuff is from
Italy; it just is, you know?"

00:14:52.030 --> 00:14:55.460
"It's the fun of collecting, and
I've always been a collector."

00:14:55.460 --> 00:14:58.630
"GILBERT: When people
are asked what would most
improve their lives,"

00:14:58.630 --> 00:15:01.200
they almost always
say more money.

00:15:01.200 --> 00:15:04.000
But are they right?

00:15:04.000 --> 00:15:06.060
Weve done a lot of research
on money and happiness

00:15:06.060 --> 00:15:08.600
over the last couple of
decades and what we find is

00:15:08.600 --> 00:15:12.130
coming out of poverty
increases your happiness.

00:15:12.130 --> 00:15:15.400
"So, if you take somebody
who wins a lottery,"

00:15:15.400 --> 00:15:18.760
"and they were in financial
trouble, they had no money,"

00:15:18.760 --> 00:15:21.960
it could make a significant
difference to their happiness.

00:15:21.960 --> 00:15:25.000
"Now, on the other hand, what if
the richest man in the world"

00:15:25.000 --> 00:15:27.400
wins a hundred-million lottery?

00:15:27.400 --> 00:15:29.630
"And now, instead of
having 50 billion,"

00:15:29.630 --> 00:15:31.530
he has 50 billion and
a hundred million.

00:15:31.530 --> 00:15:33.000
It's nothing.

00:15:33.000 --> 00:15:35.760
"So, it really does make a
difference where you start"

00:15:35.760 --> 00:15:39.160
in terms of what kind of
impact money will make.

00:15:39.160 --> 00:15:42.460
"GILBERT: When
it comes to happiness,
every dollar you earn"

00:15:42.460 --> 00:15:45.330
buys just a little bit
less than the last one.

00:15:45.330 --> 00:15:47.460
"Of course, if money
doesnt make you happy,"

00:15:47.460 --> 00:15:50.060
then you just might not
be spending it right.

00:15:50.060 --> 00:15:53.130
What we know about
lottery winners is that

00:15:53.130 --> 00:15:56.160
"when they make changes in their
life and lose their friends,"

00:15:56.160 --> 00:16:00.660
when they make changes in
their life and misspend money

00:16:00.660 --> 00:16:03.100
"on drugs, and so forth,
from a number of cases,"

00:16:03.100 --> 00:16:04.900
we know that that's going
to make you unhappy.

00:16:04.900 --> 00:16:10.130
"On the other hand, some people
who use their money correctly,"

00:16:10.130 --> 00:16:12.900
"and they use their money
to help their family,"

00:16:12.900 --> 00:16:14.860
"they use their money
to help charity,"

00:16:14.860 --> 00:16:17.160
those kind of people
can be happier.

00:16:17.160 --> 00:16:18.730
"The thought came to me,"

00:16:18.730 --> 00:16:20.500
"""Oh, my goodness, Ill
be able to, you know,"

00:16:20.500 --> 00:16:22.100
"""send my niece and
nephew to college."

00:16:22.100 --> 00:16:23.830
"I'll be able to
pay for college."""

00:16:23.830 --> 00:16:25.560
And I got weak in the knees.

00:16:25.560 --> 00:16:28.330
I never would have thought Id
be able to give them anything

00:16:28.330 --> 00:16:31.330
but flying kites...

00:16:31.330 --> 00:16:32.600
(laughs)

00:16:32.600 --> 00:16:35.500
an occasional electrified
train or something.

00:16:35.500 --> 00:16:36.860
"I mean, heres the idea"

00:16:36.860 --> 00:16:43.860
"that they can go to
college, and any college."

00:16:43.860 --> 00:16:47.030
"Oh, did the new money
strain any relationships?"

00:16:47.030 --> 00:16:49.000
"Yes, quite a few."

00:16:49.000 --> 00:16:51.160
There were friends
that Ive had...

00:16:51.160 --> 00:16:52.860
"you know, well, all these..."

00:16:52.860 --> 00:16:59.460
"all my friends were struggling
painters, writers, singers,"

00:16:59.460 --> 00:17:01.030
"performance artists, whatever,"

00:17:01.030 --> 00:17:02.630
and a few of them
couldn't handle it.

00:17:02.630 --> 00:17:05.560
All of a sudden I became
something else to them

00:17:05.560 --> 00:17:07.430
and they just
couldn't handle it.

00:17:07.430 --> 00:17:09.800
Why?

00:17:09.800 --> 00:17:11.500
"I don't know, cause
we stopped speaking."

00:17:11.500 --> 00:17:13.360
"But you know, there are other
friends who did hang around"

00:17:13.360 --> 00:17:14.760
and were still friends.

00:17:14.760 --> 00:17:17.360
WOMAN: Hes very open.

00:17:17.360 --> 00:17:20.000
You dont meet people that are
as open as he is that often.

00:17:20.000 --> 00:17:24.630
"John is a person you can laugh
with, you can get serious with,"

00:17:24.630 --> 00:17:26.130
you can argue with.

00:17:26.130 --> 00:17:29.400
"And hes just a very
stimulating, fun,"

00:17:29.400 --> 00:17:31.030
interesting man.

00:17:31.030 --> 00:17:35.530
GILBERT: Lois Mirviss is one of
John Falcon's oldest friends.

00:17:35.530 --> 00:17:38.560
She met him 20 years ago when
both were struggling artists.

00:17:38.560 --> 00:17:40.460
"MIRVISS: Wow, these
are beautiful."

00:17:40.460 --> 00:17:42.700
"GILBERT: After John won
the lottery, he hired Lois"

00:17:42.700 --> 00:17:44.730
to help design and
decorate his home.

00:17:44.730 --> 00:17:46.860
It needs to be longer
or thicker or something

00:17:46.860 --> 00:17:48.660
just to be a little
more presentational.

00:17:48.660 --> 00:17:50.760
But it's a beautiful doorknob.

00:17:50.760 --> 00:17:53.330
MIRVISS: I dont know if I've
ever told this to John.

00:17:53.330 --> 00:17:54.960
When my husband came
home and told me

00:17:54.960 --> 00:17:58.500
"that John had won the lottery,
I got very concerned."

00:17:58.500 --> 00:18:00.400
"I thought, ""Oh, poor John."

00:18:00.400 --> 00:18:01.900
"What a responsibility."""

00:18:01.900 --> 00:18:03.260
Money is fun.

00:18:03.260 --> 00:18:05.430
"Money gives you the freedom
to do all kinds of things,"

00:18:05.430 --> 00:18:07.030
but its also a burden.

00:18:07.030 --> 00:18:09.330
And I've always
impressed with John.

00:18:09.330 --> 00:18:11.430
I have to give him
credit for that.

00:18:11.430 --> 00:18:14.200
"He's a frivolous man,
but hes not foolish."

00:18:14.200 --> 00:18:18.260
And Ive watched him
take this responsibility

00:18:18.260 --> 00:18:23.000
and to have fun and yet be
supportive to his family.

00:18:23.000 --> 00:18:25.960
"So, hes taken all
of these elements"

00:18:25.960 --> 00:18:29.330
"that are quite often misused,
and he's used them very well."

00:18:29.330 --> 00:18:32.530
It takes a lot more
work to be happy

00:18:32.530 --> 00:18:35.100
"than it does to be
unhappy, to be miserable."

00:18:35.100 --> 00:18:36.860
Misery is so easy.

00:18:36.860 --> 00:18:39.300
You can just go right into it.

00:18:39.300 --> 00:18:40.830
"""I'm unhappy about this."

00:18:40.830 --> 00:18:43.230
"""I don't like that color;
I dont like scallops."

00:18:43.230 --> 00:18:44.730
"I don't like..."""

00:18:44.730 --> 00:18:46.430
"You can just go right
into it, and just..."

00:18:46.430 --> 00:18:48.730
"it snowballs, it snowballs."

00:18:48.730 --> 00:18:53.200
But being happy/content
takes work.

00:18:53.200 --> 00:18:56.860
You have to work at it.

00:18:56.860 --> 00:18:59.230
"Yeah, I think so
far it's been fun."

00:18:59.230 --> 00:19:01.730
But is it a life well lived?

00:19:01.730 --> 00:19:04.130
I don't think a life well
lived depends on money.

00:19:04.130 --> 00:19:06.030
"So, I don't know if
my life is well lived."

00:19:06.030 --> 00:19:08.630
I think other people
have to judge that.

00:19:08.630 --> 00:19:10.100
Anyone that tells you

00:19:10.100 --> 00:19:14.860
"money doesnt bring happiness
is an ass, is a fool."

00:19:14.860 --> 00:19:17.060
I think what happens
with more money

00:19:17.060 --> 00:19:19.560
"is that there are
more highs available,"

00:19:19.560 --> 00:19:23.860
"so theres more access to
shopping, drugs, trips,"

00:19:23.860 --> 00:19:27.260
theres more access to highs.

00:19:27.260 --> 00:19:31.960
"So if we call that happiness,
yeah, more available."

00:19:31.960 --> 00:19:33.800
(laughs) But I don't
call that happiness.

00:19:33.800 --> 00:19:37.330
"There is no key to happiness
in my book, except maybe,"

00:19:37.330 --> 00:19:42.100
"you know, another $20 million
film, which will never happen."

00:19:42.100 --> 00:19:43.530
(laughs)

00:19:43.530 --> 00:19:46.130
"So, I can't look forward to,
like, great happiness ahead."

00:19:46.130 --> 00:19:50.630
Money can't buy you fulfillment.

00:19:50.630 --> 00:19:55.460
"It can, at some times,
buy you peace of mind,"

00:19:55.460 --> 00:20:01.330
"but it cant make you a happier
person and, in some ways,"

00:20:01.330 --> 00:20:08.830
knowing that makes you even
less of a happy person.

00:20:08.830 --> 00:20:12.160
"GILBERT: So, what is
the relationship between
money and happiness?"

00:20:12.160 --> 00:20:14.630
"Well, most of us think that if
we were a whole lot richer,"

00:20:14.630 --> 00:20:16.400
wed be a whole lot happier.

00:20:16.400 --> 00:20:19.330
But research shows this
isn't necessarily true.

00:20:19.330 --> 00:20:22.560
"So, why do we all believe it?"

00:20:22.560 --> 00:20:24.100
"Well, as it turns out,"

00:20:24.100 --> 00:20:25.800
people arent very
good at predicting

00:20:25.800 --> 00:20:28.630
what will and won't
make them happy.

00:20:28.630 --> 00:20:30.900
"In a recent experiment,"

00:20:30.900 --> 00:20:33.000
researchers went
to a health club

00:20:33.000 --> 00:20:35.100
and asked a simple question.

00:20:35.100 --> 00:20:37.830
Youre gonna live in the woods
for two days and two nights.

00:20:37.830 --> 00:20:40.300
"You can have food or
water but not both,"

00:20:40.300 --> 00:20:41.760
which would you rather have?

00:20:41.760 --> 00:20:43.330
Food or water?

00:20:43.330 --> 00:20:44.360
Food.

00:20:44.360 --> 00:20:47.360
"Uh, I'd say food."

00:20:47.360 --> 00:20:49.930
"Okay, circle that."

00:20:49.930 --> 00:20:52.030
GILBERT: Some of the people
were asked this question

00:20:52.030 --> 00:20:53.360
before they worked out.

00:20:53.360 --> 00:20:56.600
Some were asked after
they worked out.

00:20:56.600 --> 00:20:57.800
And when they were asked

00:20:57.800 --> 00:21:00.630
made a huge difference
in how they answered.

00:21:00.630 --> 00:21:04.800
"In fact, people were 50%
more likely to say ""water"""

00:21:04.800 --> 00:21:06.700
if theyd just
finished working out

00:21:06.700 --> 00:21:08.030
than if they were
about to start.

00:21:08.030 --> 00:21:09.130
Water.

00:21:09.130 --> 00:21:10.530
Definitely water.

00:21:10.530 --> 00:21:12.260
GILBERT: Why?

00:21:12.260 --> 00:21:14.500
"People were thirsty
after exercising,"

00:21:14.500 --> 00:21:16.130
"and because they
were thirsty now,"

00:21:16.130 --> 00:21:19.600
they imagined being
thirsty in the future.

00:21:19.600 --> 00:21:22.560
This is something our
brains do all the time.

00:21:22.560 --> 00:21:25.430
"When we think about how
well feel in the future,"

00:21:25.430 --> 00:21:28.960
our thoughts are shaped by
how we feel in the present.

00:21:28.960 --> 00:21:32.260
Its as if our brains cant
believe that we might feel

00:21:32.260 --> 00:21:35.760
differently later
than we do now.

00:21:35.760 --> 00:21:39.860
Thats not the only thing our
brains cant quite believe.

00:21:39.860 --> 00:21:43.100
We all know that feelings
inevitably change over time--

00:21:43.100 --> 00:21:45.760
"that new love fades,
that fresh wounds heal."

00:21:45.760 --> 00:21:49.830
"And yet, when we imagine our
future joys and future sorrows,"

00:21:49.830 --> 00:21:53.500
we tend not to think about
how time will change them.

00:21:53.500 --> 00:21:55.360
We sure do have the
compelling intuition

00:21:55.360 --> 00:22:00.460
"that somehow improving our life
circumstances, our situations,"

00:22:00.460 --> 00:22:04.060
"whether it has to
do with relationships
or jobs or health,"

00:22:04.060 --> 00:22:05.800
that that's going
to make us happier.

00:22:05.800 --> 00:22:07.960
"And the truth is that
it does make us happier,"

00:22:07.960 --> 00:22:10.530
but it doesnt make us happier
for as long or as intensely

00:22:10.530 --> 00:22:12.000
as we think it would.

00:22:12.000 --> 00:22:15.200
GILBERT: Psychologist
Sonja Lyubomirsky suggests

00:22:15.200 --> 00:22:18.060
that were sadly mistaken when
we expect that the things

00:22:18.060 --> 00:22:19.930
that make us happy for a day

00:22:19.930 --> 00:22:22.760
will make us happy
for a lifetime.

00:22:22.760 --> 00:22:25.360
"LYUBOMIRSKY: Its a phenomenon
called hedonic adaptation,"

00:22:25.360 --> 00:22:29.100
which means that human
beings basically are just

00:22:29.100 --> 00:22:31.260
"incredibly good at
getting used to,"

00:22:31.260 --> 00:22:34.200
"getting accustomed to,
adapting positive changes,"

00:22:34.200 --> 00:22:38.260
"especially in their lives, like
the new car or the new house."

00:22:38.260 --> 00:22:41.730
And so thats one of the
reasons that we keep

00:22:41.730 --> 00:22:43.960
sort of buying more
stuff is that we...

00:22:43.960 --> 00:22:46.160
"you know, we get the handbag,
that gives us a boost."

00:22:46.160 --> 00:22:48.560
It wears off and then
we get a new handbag.

00:22:48.560 --> 00:22:51.760
GILBERT: Adaptation
affects our experience

00:22:51.760 --> 00:22:53.460
of both good things
and bad things

00:22:53.460 --> 00:22:57.060
in ways that we find
difficult to anticipate.

00:22:57.060 --> 00:22:59.060
This is something my colleagues
and I have been studying

00:22:59.060 --> 00:23:00.500
in the lab.

00:23:00.500 --> 00:23:02.700
And wed be very happy to
give you one as a gift

00:23:02.700 --> 00:23:04.430
for participating
in the experiment.

00:23:04.430 --> 00:23:05.930
Which one would
you like to have?

00:23:05.930 --> 00:23:09.700
"GILBERT: In one experiment,
we brought people into a room"

00:23:09.700 --> 00:23:12.830
filled with art posters and
offered to give them one.

00:23:12.830 --> 00:23:15.230
We told half of the participants

00:23:15.230 --> 00:23:17.900
that their decision
was irreversible

00:23:17.900 --> 00:23:19.560
"and that once theyd made it,"

00:23:19.560 --> 00:23:21.400
they could never
change their minds.

00:23:21.400 --> 00:23:24.430
We told the other half that
they could exchange the poster

00:23:24.430 --> 00:23:27.200
they chose for a different
poster any time they wanted.

00:23:27.200 --> 00:23:29.800
"After making their choices,"

00:23:29.800 --> 00:23:32.500
we asked both groups
to rank their posters.

00:23:32.500 --> 00:23:34.060
And guess what?

00:23:34.060 --> 00:23:36.100
The people who knew they
couldnt exchange their posters

00:23:36.100 --> 00:23:39.530
liked them more than the
people who knew they could.

00:23:39.530 --> 00:23:42.830
Why? Because they had no choice.

00:23:42.830 --> 00:23:45.030
And so they adapted.

00:23:45.030 --> 00:23:47.430
The lesson of this
study was clear:

00:23:47.430 --> 00:23:50.930
people find ways to like things
when they're stuck with them.

00:23:50.930 --> 00:23:53.330
"When we cant change
our circumstances,"

00:23:53.330 --> 00:23:56.230
we change the way we think
about those circumstances.

00:23:56.230 --> 00:23:59.860
And yet most of us dont seem
to realize this will happen.

00:23:59.860 --> 00:24:04.230
MAN: Theres a part of me that is

00:24:04.230 --> 00:24:07.060
the most hyper person ever.

00:24:07.060 --> 00:24:09.400
"The minute I was
born, I was running."

00:24:09.400 --> 00:24:10.860
I was like a Red Bull baby.

00:24:10.860 --> 00:24:14.530
GILBERT: Francesco Clark was
a young man with big dreams

00:24:14.530 --> 00:24:17.800
when he moved to New York City
to take a job in publishing.

00:24:17.800 --> 00:24:19.430
CLARK: It was very exciting.

00:24:19.430 --> 00:24:23.000
"It was movies, it was
television, it was celebrities,"

00:24:23.000 --> 00:24:25.500
it was everything that

00:24:25.500 --> 00:24:30.300
a 22-year-old graduating
college kind of dreams of.

00:24:30.300 --> 00:24:33.600
"GILBERT: Then, in
the blink of an eye,"

00:24:33.600 --> 00:24:35.900
his life was forever
transformed.

00:24:35.900 --> 00:24:38.860
"CLARK: I had a summer rental,
and I get to the house"

00:24:38.860 --> 00:24:40.400
and there's a pool.

00:24:40.400 --> 00:24:43.300
"And it was a nice summer day,"

00:24:43.300 --> 00:24:46.500
so naturally I wanted
to go swimming.

00:24:46.500 --> 00:24:49.430
"The second that I
dove into the pool,"

00:24:49.430 --> 00:24:53.300
my chin hit the bottom
and my head snapped back.

00:24:53.300 --> 00:25:00.100
"In one millisecond, my
life changed completely."

00:25:00.100 --> 00:25:04.000
I was told I was going to
die three times that night.

00:25:04.000 --> 00:25:07.000
I couldn't breathe on my own.

00:25:07.000 --> 00:25:08.160
I was on a ventilator.

00:25:08.160 --> 00:25:10.900
I had a tube going
down my mouth.

00:25:10.900 --> 00:25:13.030
GILBERT: Francescos doctors said

00:25:13.030 --> 00:25:15.530
that hed never be
able to move again.

00:25:15.530 --> 00:25:17.830
CLARK: I was depressed
after the accident.

00:25:17.830 --> 00:25:19.560
"That's a pretty
big change of life,"

00:25:19.560 --> 00:25:22.930
"to then suddenly not be
able to eat on your own,"

00:25:22.930 --> 00:25:25.800
"or not be able
to brush your teeth, or
to go to the bathroom."

00:25:25.800 --> 00:25:28.160
"Its... you know, theres
a sense of embarrassment"

00:25:28.160 --> 00:25:31.530
that comes with it at first.

00:25:31.530 --> 00:25:33.230
"When you cant feed yourself,"

00:25:33.230 --> 00:25:38.200
"when you cant scratch your
nose, it can drive you crazy."

00:25:38.200 --> 00:25:41.000
"So, I just wanted to fix it."

00:25:41.000 --> 00:25:42.400
"I just wanted to, you know,"

00:25:42.400 --> 00:25:44.330
show them that I was
gonna get better.

00:25:44.330 --> 00:25:45.660
I had to; I had no choice.

00:25:45.660 --> 00:25:47.160
"I mean, what are you gonna do?"

00:25:47.160 --> 00:25:48.800
Are you just gonna sit?

00:25:48.800 --> 00:25:51.060
You're just gonna lay
in bed and wither away?

00:25:51.060 --> 00:25:52.360
I didn't... I didn't
want to do that.

00:25:52.360 --> 00:26:02.160
I wanted to... I wanted to live.

00:26:02.160 --> 00:26:03.760
I started to feel better.

00:26:03.760 --> 00:26:07.360
"It wasnt a specific day and
it wasnt a specific time,"

00:26:07.360 --> 00:26:11.800
"but I realized that it wasnt
about my injury anymore,"

00:26:11.800 --> 00:26:15.130
and it wasnt about this
metal frame that I sit on.

00:26:15.130 --> 00:26:17.830
"It was more about, ""What do
I want to do with my life?"""

00:26:17.830 --> 00:26:21.860
"GILBERT: After his
accident, Francesco moved
back in with his parents"

00:26:21.860 --> 00:26:25.200
and began devoting long
hours to a grueling routine

00:26:25.200 --> 00:26:27.000
of physical therapy.

00:26:27.000 --> 00:26:31.000
CLARK: I do very intensive
physical therapy every day.

00:26:31.000 --> 00:26:36.260
I pedal the special bike
with my arms and my legs.

00:26:36.260 --> 00:26:38.260
I sit up.

00:26:38.260 --> 00:26:40.500
I am relearning how to crawl.

00:26:40.500 --> 00:26:43.560
"When I started to
move my arms again,"

00:26:43.560 --> 00:26:48.730
"you know, six months before,"

00:26:48.730 --> 00:26:52.560
"""Oh, you know, I can't
move my arm, that sucks."""

00:26:52.560 --> 00:26:55.530
"But then moving it
again makes you realize,"

00:26:55.530 --> 00:26:58.960
"""Oh, my God, you know,
this is incredible."

00:26:58.960 --> 00:27:01.300
"""I can't believe I'm
starting to use my wrist."

00:27:01.300 --> 00:27:03.500
"I can't believe I'm
moving my arm."""

00:27:03.500 --> 00:27:05.130
"I mean, you're
moving your arm."

00:27:05.130 --> 00:27:07.100
"When you dont have a
spinal cord injury,"

00:27:07.100 --> 00:27:08.700
"you dont think about,"

00:27:08.700 --> 00:27:12.130
"""God, Im so thankful
that I can breathe out
of my left lung."""

00:27:12.130 --> 00:27:14.560
"I mean, you just... you
never think about that."

00:27:14.560 --> 00:27:17.300
"GILBERT: In the years since,"

00:27:17.300 --> 00:27:21.730
Francesco has learned to move
a lot more than just his body.

00:27:21.730 --> 00:27:24.330
CLARK: I started a skin care
line called Clarks Botanicals.

00:27:24.330 --> 00:27:26.400
That started because
of my injury.

00:27:26.400 --> 00:27:29.030
I lost the ability to sweat.

00:27:29.030 --> 00:27:33.460
"It looked like I had specks
of sand under each pore,"

00:27:33.460 --> 00:27:36.630
"and it was red, it was flaky,
it was gray, it was sensitive."

00:27:36.630 --> 00:27:38.160
It looked like it was aging.

00:27:38.160 --> 00:27:40.930
"I was kind of like, ""Well, Ive
tried everything prescription,"

00:27:40.930 --> 00:27:42.560
"Ive tried everything
over the counter."""

00:27:42.560 --> 00:27:45.600
I started to look at essential
oils and botanical extracts.

00:27:45.600 --> 00:27:50.400
"So, I had these, like, ugly
little vials that I would use."

00:27:50.400 --> 00:27:52.060
"And then my sister
started using it,"

00:27:52.060 --> 00:27:53.530
and then my mom started using it

00:27:53.530 --> 00:27:55.000
and then my dad's patients
started using it.

00:27:55.000 --> 00:27:56.760
"And then I was kind
of like, ""Hold on."

00:27:56.760 --> 00:27:58.130
"""You know, this isnt, like..."

00:27:58.130 --> 00:27:59.660
"""Im just making
this in the kitchen."

00:27:59.660 --> 00:28:01.200
"I don't know what I'm doing."""

00:28:01.200 --> 00:28:05.200
"So, it was very much an organic
evolution of my injury."

00:28:05.200 --> 00:28:09.200
"GILBERT: Today,
Francescos products are
sold all over the world"

00:28:09.200 --> 00:28:11.700
and he has the
schedule of a busy CEO:

00:28:11.700 --> 00:28:14.060
"running his own
firm, writing a book"

00:28:14.060 --> 00:28:16.130
and working with the
Christopher Reeve Foundation

00:28:16.130 --> 00:28:18.800
as an advocate for
people with disabilities.

00:28:18.800 --> 00:28:21.660
CLARK: I'm very happy now.

00:28:21.660 --> 00:28:28.000
"I love every aspect of my
life, from work to my friends"

00:28:28.000 --> 00:28:31.260
to being with my family
to thinking about

00:28:31.260 --> 00:28:33.400
living an independent life.

00:28:33.400 --> 00:28:37.400
I'm still pretty much
exactly who I was before.

00:28:37.400 --> 00:28:41.000
"I laugh at the same jokes,
I love the same movies."

00:28:41.000 --> 00:28:44.800
"I have the same
sense of curiosity,"

00:28:44.800 --> 00:28:49.160
but I think that
everything is more...

00:28:49.160 --> 00:28:51.260
(sighs)

00:28:51.260 --> 00:28:53.830
"I don't know, Im just as
stupid as I was before."

00:28:53.830 --> 00:28:58.330
It's just that I've
learned more about myself.

00:28:58.330 --> 00:29:02.430
"GILBERT: The ability to
bounce back is admirable,
but it isnt unusual."

00:29:02.430 --> 00:29:05.500
People who suffer a wide range
of traumas and tragedies

00:29:05.500 --> 00:29:07.030
tend to recover more quickly

00:29:07.030 --> 00:29:09.400
than they themselves
would have predicted.

00:29:09.400 --> 00:29:11.730
"Yes, theyre sad,
theyre miserable,"

00:29:11.730 --> 00:29:13.730
"theyre even devastated
for a while,"

00:29:13.730 --> 00:29:16.900
but studies show that most
people end up being as happy

00:29:16.900 --> 00:29:20.130
or nearly as happy
as they were before.

00:29:20.130 --> 00:29:21.930
Resilience isn't rare.

00:29:21.930 --> 00:29:24.660
"In fact, its very common."

00:29:24.660 --> 00:29:26.700
There is some set
point to happiness

00:29:26.700 --> 00:29:28.230
that you tend to return toward

00:29:28.230 --> 00:29:29.900
and for some people
its very happy

00:29:29.900 --> 00:29:31.830
and for other people
its mildly happy.

00:29:31.830 --> 00:29:35.200
"And unfortunately, for a few
people it may not be happy."

00:29:35.200 --> 00:29:38.700
But the set point is
good in the sense that

00:29:38.700 --> 00:29:41.860
"when we have something terrible
in our life happen to us,"

00:29:41.860 --> 00:29:44.900
"we get very depressed, we get
less satisfied with our life,"

00:29:44.900 --> 00:29:49.660
"but slowly, over time, we come
back toward that set point."

00:29:49.660 --> 00:29:53.160
GILBERT: This process is
critical to human happiness.

00:29:53.160 --> 00:29:55.460
But how do we do it?

00:29:55.460 --> 00:30:00.060
And why do some of us do it so
much more easily than others?

00:30:00.060 --> 00:30:03.530
"For more than 15 years,
Dr. Dennis Charney"

00:30:03.530 --> 00:30:06.060
has been studying people whove
shown exceptional resilience

00:30:06.060 --> 00:30:08.000
"after trauma,"

00:30:08.000 --> 00:30:10.500
from survivors of
natural disasters...

00:30:10.500 --> 00:30:13.200
to prisoners of war...

00:30:13.200 --> 00:30:14.960
to the firemen who responded

00:30:14.960 --> 00:30:19.260
when the World Trade Center
was attacked on September 11.

00:30:19.260 --> 00:30:21.460
CHARNEY: It was fascinating to
deal with resilient individuals

00:30:21.460 --> 00:30:24.200
"because when you met them, you
looked at them and thought,"

00:30:24.200 --> 00:30:26.330
"""Well, how did you...
how did you do this?"""

00:30:26.330 --> 00:30:27.760
"You start thinking,
""Could I have done that?"

00:30:27.760 --> 00:30:29.260
"How did they do it?"""

00:30:29.260 --> 00:30:32.230
GILBERT: One of Charneys
most interesting subjects

00:30:32.230 --> 00:30:35.600
"was Bob Shumaker, a
former Navy pilot."

00:30:35.600 --> 00:30:38.330
SHUMAKER: I grew up on a
farm in western Pennsylvania.

00:30:38.330 --> 00:30:39.630
"My parents were middle class,"

00:30:39.630 --> 00:30:42.600
so I consider myself
fairly average.

00:30:42.600 --> 00:30:47.330
But average people get thrown
into extraordinary situations.

00:30:47.330 --> 00:30:50.730
"GILBERT: Bobs ordeal
began in 1965,"

00:30:50.730 --> 00:30:54.230
when he was assigned to
combat duty in Vietnam.

00:30:54.230 --> 00:30:56.160
Hed just been married
and had a son.

00:30:56.160 --> 00:30:59.400
"Then, suddenly, life as
he knew it came to an end."

00:30:59.400 --> 00:31:01.300
SHUMAKER: The mission I was on

00:31:01.300 --> 00:31:03.860
was just north of the
demilitarized zone

00:31:03.860 --> 00:31:06.300
that separated North
Vietnam from South Vietnam.

00:31:06.300 --> 00:31:10.860
We were really low and I pulled
out right over a flak site.

00:31:10.860 --> 00:31:13.360
(explosions)

00:31:13.360 --> 00:31:15.060
And they managed to hit
me in the tail section

00:31:15.060 --> 00:31:17.130
and the plane
flipped upside down

00:31:17.130 --> 00:31:20.660
"and I ejected and the
parachute fortunately opened,"

00:31:20.660 --> 00:31:23.500
but opened only 35
feet above the ground

00:31:23.500 --> 00:31:29.660
and so I broke my
back as I landed.

00:31:29.660 --> 00:31:32.860
"That was it, you know,
they got me, they bound me,"

00:31:32.860 --> 00:31:37.660
had handcuffs on me behind
my back and marched me off.

00:31:37.660 --> 00:31:39.230
"GILBERT: For eight years,
Shumaker was shuttled"

00:31:39.230 --> 00:31:41.500
"between North
Vietnamese prisons,"

00:31:41.500 --> 00:31:43.460
"including the
infamous Hanoi Hilton,"

00:31:43.460 --> 00:31:45.660
where he was brutally tortured.

00:31:45.660 --> 00:31:48.400
SHUMAKER: The really worst
technique was what wed call

00:31:48.400 --> 00:31:50.660
"the rope treatment, where
they would tie a rope"

00:31:50.660 --> 00:31:52.330
"from your handcuffs,
up over your shoulders,"

00:31:52.330 --> 00:31:54.030
"and down to your feet,"

00:31:54.030 --> 00:31:56.030
and they would
tighten this thing up

00:31:56.030 --> 00:31:59.260
so that eventually your
head would reach your feet.

00:31:59.260 --> 00:32:01.700
"And you think it cant
happen, you know,"

00:32:01.700 --> 00:32:04.000
"particularly when your
knees are straight, but..."

00:32:04.000 --> 00:32:05.500
"it was excruciating,"

00:32:05.500 --> 00:32:07.730
and then they jammed an
iron bar down my throat

00:32:07.730 --> 00:32:09.560
to keep me from screaming.

00:32:09.560 --> 00:32:12.260
"So, that was the technique
that would get you to condemn"

00:32:12.260 --> 00:32:15.960
your own grandmother
if you had to.

00:32:15.960 --> 00:32:19.660
GILBERT: The torture Shumaker
endured was not just physical.

00:32:19.660 --> 00:32:24.160
"For almost three years, he was
held in solitary confinement."

00:32:24.160 --> 00:32:26.830
"SHUMAKER: There were 11
of us in cells, no windows"

00:32:26.830 --> 00:32:28.600
and a solitary light
bulb hanging down

00:32:28.600 --> 00:32:29.800
that burned 24 hours a day.

00:32:29.800 --> 00:32:32.600
"GILBERT: To deal
with his isolation,"

00:32:32.600 --> 00:32:35.260
Shumaker imagined the
house that he would build

00:32:35.260 --> 00:32:38.130
for his young family
if he ever returned.

00:32:38.130 --> 00:32:42.700
Im almost embarrassed to admit
to you that there would be days

00:32:42.700 --> 00:32:45.460
when I would spend
maybe ten or 12 hours

00:32:45.460 --> 00:32:48.600
just thinking about how many
bricks were in this house.

00:32:48.600 --> 00:32:53.830
"I knew that there were, say,
5,227 nails in the thing,"

00:32:53.830 --> 00:32:56.660
so many board feet of lumber.

00:32:56.660 --> 00:32:59.430
Id spend a year and a half
designing the perfect house

00:32:59.430 --> 00:33:01.930
"and then one day Id say,
""Well, what would happen"

00:33:01.930 --> 00:33:05.400
"if I moved the fireplace from
this room to that room?"""

00:33:05.400 --> 00:33:08.860
Itd send me back to square one
and I'd redesign the thing.

00:33:08.860 --> 00:33:11.400
GILBERT: Although Shumaker
was physically isolated

00:33:11.400 --> 00:33:13.730
"from the other prisoners,"

00:33:13.730 --> 00:33:17.000
together they created an
ingenious form of communication.

00:33:17.000 --> 00:33:21.630
SHUMAKER: We developed
a tap code in which the
alphabet was arranged

00:33:21.630 --> 00:33:25.030
in a square that had five
rows and five columns.

00:33:25.030 --> 00:33:28.160
Youd say (tapping)...

00:33:28.160 --> 00:33:29.460
"thats the second
row, second column,"

00:33:29.460 --> 00:33:30.630
"this is ""G""."

00:33:30.630 --> 00:33:32.800
(tapping)

00:33:32.800 --> 00:33:34.760
"First row, second
column-- ""B""--"

00:33:34.760 --> 00:33:36.160
"and ""U"" is..."

00:33:36.160 --> 00:33:38.260
(tapping)

00:33:38.260 --> 00:33:40.130
"Fourth row, fifth
column is the ""U"","

00:33:40.130 --> 00:33:41.800
"so ""GBU"" was
""God bless you."""

00:33:41.800 --> 00:33:46.660
"So the tap code really
kept our spirits alive,"

00:33:46.660 --> 00:33:48.860
"our hopes alive, our dreams."

00:33:48.860 --> 00:33:53.400
So we transmitted things like
French lessons through the wall

00:33:53.400 --> 00:33:57.130
and music lessons and how
to fix a television set

00:33:57.130 --> 00:34:00.300
"and biology lessons,"

00:34:00.300 --> 00:34:03.330
so we spent a lot
of time on the wall.

00:34:03.330 --> 00:34:07.560
"GILBERT: These
conversations were crucial
to Shumakers survival,"

00:34:07.560 --> 00:34:10.430
and they became a focus of
Dennis Charneys research.

00:34:10.430 --> 00:34:12.800
CHARNEY: Social
support is a key factor

00:34:12.800 --> 00:34:14.900
in becoming a
resilient individual.

00:34:14.900 --> 00:34:16.700
You can't do it alone.

00:34:16.700 --> 00:34:19.430
You need other people.

00:34:19.430 --> 00:34:22.160
I think the tap code
experience of the POWs

00:34:22.160 --> 00:34:25.560
is among the most
important lessons.

00:34:25.560 --> 00:34:28.430
"And we use the phrase,
""Everybody needs a tap code."""

00:34:28.430 --> 00:34:31.660
Everybody needs a way of
communicating with other people

00:34:31.660 --> 00:34:35.160
"to establish friendships
that are supportive,"

00:34:35.160 --> 00:34:38.600
"to establish relationships
that provide you a guidepost,"

00:34:38.600 --> 00:34:41.160
as you get through tough times.

00:34:41.160 --> 00:34:44.630
GILBERT: Charney also discovered
that highly resilient people

00:34:44.630 --> 00:34:46.930
tended to share some
other qualities as well.

00:34:46.930 --> 00:34:50.460
"They tended to have strong
religious or moral beliefs,"

00:34:50.460 --> 00:34:53.800
"strong role models, and a
strong streak of optimism."

00:34:53.800 --> 00:34:56.100
It was not a
unrealistic optimism.

00:34:56.100 --> 00:34:59.530
They were able to accurately
apprise themselves

00:34:59.530 --> 00:35:01.200
of what they were facing.

00:35:01.200 --> 00:35:04.000
"So, it wasnt denial."

00:35:04.000 --> 00:35:06.760
They knew that they
had been traumatized

00:35:06.760 --> 00:35:09.800
or they were facing a
very difficult situation.

00:35:09.800 --> 00:35:13.130
"But they had an ability
to be optimistic,"

00:35:13.130 --> 00:35:16.230
that somehow that
they would prevail.

00:35:16.230 --> 00:35:19.530
SHUMAKER: I only received
seven letters in eight years

00:35:19.530 --> 00:35:22.830
"and the letters were...
occasionally were pessimistic,"

00:35:22.830 --> 00:35:24.960
like telling me my
mother had suddenly died

00:35:24.960 --> 00:35:26.930
and things like that.

00:35:26.930 --> 00:35:30.230
"And you just have to be able
to, you know, just suck it up"

00:35:30.230 --> 00:35:33.630
and reach down
somewhere in your soul

00:35:33.630 --> 00:35:37.460
and come out with the
wherewithal to overcome

00:35:37.460 --> 00:35:42.130
the present circumstances and
be upbeat and get on with it.

00:35:42.130 --> 00:35:45.500
"GILBERT: After eight
years of captivity,"

00:35:45.500 --> 00:35:47.760
"Bob Shumaker was
finally released,"

00:35:47.760 --> 00:35:51.030
his spirit unbroken by
the horrors he endured.

00:35:51.030 --> 00:35:54.300
The first thing he
did was call his wife.

00:35:54.300 --> 00:35:57.760
WOMAN: I wondered
who this man was.

00:35:57.760 --> 00:36:00.130
I didnt know him very much.

00:36:00.130 --> 00:36:03.660
We had a very short courtship.

00:36:03.660 --> 00:36:06.800
Our baby was born
just five weeks

00:36:06.800 --> 00:36:10.860
before Bob was shot
down and captured.

00:36:10.860 --> 00:36:12.700
"I remember this
phone call saying,"

00:36:12.700 --> 00:36:18.700
"""Hi, honey,"" and
that literally erased
eight years of time."

00:36:18.700 --> 00:36:25.400
"It's hard to explain that, but
that was the person I knew."

00:36:25.400 --> 00:36:30.830
And that was the person
that returned home.

00:36:30.830 --> 00:36:33.830
GILBERT: Shumaker had done
more than just survive.

00:36:33.830 --> 00:36:36.230
"In his view, he had grown."

00:36:36.230 --> 00:36:38.400
I suppose one way of looking
at eight years of imprisonment

00:36:38.400 --> 00:36:41.660
"is to say, ""Hey,
thats just wasted time."

00:36:41.660 --> 00:36:45.560
"You know, I have to put that
behind me, its unfortunate."""

00:36:45.560 --> 00:36:49.830
"But, paradoxically,
I gained something"

00:36:49.830 --> 00:36:51.760
out of this eight
years of experience.

00:36:51.760 --> 00:36:54.630
"GILBERT: In the years
after his release,"

00:36:54.630 --> 00:36:57.830
"Shumaker became a rear
admiral, a college professor,"

00:36:57.830 --> 00:36:59.900
"a devoted husband and father,"

00:36:59.900 --> 00:37:02.630
and he turned the house
that hed so often imagined

00:37:02.630 --> 00:37:04.830
into a reality.

00:37:04.830 --> 00:37:08.560
"SHUMAKER: It was something in
my soul I just had to get out,"

00:37:08.560 --> 00:37:11.330
"you know, and see
to fulfillment."

00:37:11.330 --> 00:37:14.460
I wanted a house that had
a lot of openness to it

00:37:14.460 --> 00:37:16.860
and I think that was probably as
a result of my being confined

00:37:16.860 --> 00:37:18.300
"without windows or anything,"

00:37:18.300 --> 00:37:21.600
so the house I designed
has a lot of glass.

00:37:21.600 --> 00:37:24.900
"I was deprived of freedom
for such a long time,"

00:37:24.900 --> 00:37:30.130
I think I really cherish freedom
more than most people do now.

00:37:30.130 --> 00:37:32.330
"CHARNEY: Bob, like
almost all the other POWs"

00:37:32.330 --> 00:37:35.860
"that we interviewed and
got to know very well,"

00:37:35.860 --> 00:37:40.100
"said that, to the
following question,"

00:37:40.100 --> 00:37:43.930
"""If you couldve eliminated the
POW experience from your life,"

00:37:43.930 --> 00:37:45.800
"would you do so?"""

00:37:45.800 --> 00:37:47.460
"In other words, you couldve
just wiped that out,"

00:37:47.460 --> 00:37:49.030
it never happened.

00:37:49.030 --> 00:37:51.530
"And Bob, like many of
the others, said, ""No,"

00:37:51.530 --> 00:37:54.660
"""because I learned
things about myself
during that experience,"

00:37:54.660 --> 00:37:56.260
"""and I learned tools--"

00:37:56.260 --> 00:37:59.900
"""psychological tools, tools
in which to handle my life,"

00:37:59.900 --> 00:38:02.830
"""that I probably could never
have learned in any other way."

00:38:02.830 --> 00:38:09.400
"And so it stood me
in good stead for the
rest of my life."""

00:38:09.400 --> 00:38:15.100
SHUMAKER: Being a prisoner
really focuses on whats
essential in life.

00:38:15.100 --> 00:38:20.360
There are a lot of things we can
do without and still be happy.

00:38:20.360 --> 00:38:22.830
CHARNEY: The key lessons
from Bob Shumakers story

00:38:22.830 --> 00:38:28.630
are that inside almost all of
us is the capacity to overcome

00:38:28.630 --> 00:38:30.930
the most horrific of
stresses in our life

00:38:30.930 --> 00:38:34.800
and even ultimately learn
from that stress and thrive

00:38:34.800 --> 00:38:40.400
and grow as a person.

00:38:40.400 --> 00:38:44.060
MAN: You learn resilience
by falling down and
getting back up again.

00:38:44.060 --> 00:38:46.530
"And as you fall down and
get back up again, you say,"

00:38:46.530 --> 00:38:48.660
"""Oh, my God, Im...
Im back up again."

00:38:48.660 --> 00:38:51.460
"""The setback or the
failure that I thought"

00:38:51.460 --> 00:38:52.800
"""I would never recover from,"

00:38:52.800 --> 00:38:54.500
"""in fact Ive recovered
from perfectly well,"

00:38:54.500 --> 00:38:56.160
"which means that I
can do that again."""

00:38:56.160 --> 00:38:57.700
WOMAN: My resilience has been

00:38:57.700 --> 00:38:59.560
slowly learning to trust

00:38:59.560 --> 00:39:03.960
that whatever path I
take can be positive.

00:39:03.960 --> 00:39:07.860
"You know, even the worst
decisions Ive made have had,"

00:39:07.860 --> 00:39:10.600
"you know, positive
ramifications if I choose
to learn from them."

00:39:10.600 --> 00:39:12.330
"Well, I want to make
sure that people know"

00:39:12.330 --> 00:39:14.500
"that Im happy that I had
a messed-up childhood,"

00:39:14.500 --> 00:39:16.830
"that Im glad I was damaged,"

00:39:16.830 --> 00:39:20.000
"because it made
me a better actor,"

00:39:20.000 --> 00:39:23.060
"it made me a better writer,
it made me a better creator."

00:39:23.060 --> 00:39:24.860
So I thank my family for that.

00:39:24.860 --> 00:39:26.800
I wouldnt trade it for
anything in the world.

00:39:26.800 --> 00:39:30.660
"Then I would
have, but not now."

00:39:30.660 --> 00:39:32.800
"GILBERT: Human beings have
a talent for adapting,"

00:39:32.800 --> 00:39:36.100
a talent for finding happiness
where wed least expect it.

00:39:36.100 --> 00:39:38.760
But if we can adapt to a
lifetime in a wheelchair

00:39:38.760 --> 00:39:40.530
"or a decade in prison,"

00:39:40.530 --> 00:39:42.460
then why cant we adapt

00:39:42.460 --> 00:39:44.430
to the ordinary misfortunes
of everyday life?

00:39:44.430 --> 00:39:47.830
The answer is that adaptation
is something the mind does

00:39:47.830 --> 00:39:49.560
when there's nothing
else it can do.

00:39:49.560 --> 00:39:52.960
"We adapt to misfortunes when
we know we cant change them,"

00:39:52.960 --> 00:39:56.060
"but when we stand a
fighting chance, we fight."

00:39:56.060 --> 00:40:03.830
And that's why we struggle so
much with temporary misfortunes.

00:40:03.830 --> 00:40:05.760
MAN: I was always good at math.

00:40:05.760 --> 00:40:08.000
My dad worked in finance.

00:40:08.000 --> 00:40:11.030
When I was in high school
I took an economics class

00:40:11.030 --> 00:40:14.200
where you had to pick stocks
and I just always liked it.

00:40:14.200 --> 00:40:16.860
"Went to college,
studied it there."

00:40:16.860 --> 00:40:19.060
"My brother was on Wall
Street at the time,"

00:40:19.060 --> 00:40:20.530
"he helped me get my first job,"

00:40:20.530 --> 00:40:26.860
"and, uh, ten years later, here
I am, unemployed in a chair."

00:40:26.860 --> 00:40:30.800
GILBERT: Bill OConnor was a bond
salesman at Lehman Brothers

00:40:30.800 --> 00:40:34.660
when Wall Street began to
collapse in the spring of 2008.

00:40:34.660 --> 00:40:37.160
"He and his wife
Stephanie had a new baby,"

00:40:37.160 --> 00:40:39.030
"a new apartment
in New York City,"

00:40:39.030 --> 00:40:41.300
and they knew they
were in trouble.

00:40:41.300 --> 00:40:44.100
"OCONNOR: A lot of
people describe it that
when you join a bank,"

00:40:44.100 --> 00:40:48.430
"theres like a bullet and
on that day that you join,"

00:40:48.430 --> 00:40:50.630
"they inscribe your name
on it, and someday,"

00:40:50.630 --> 00:40:54.230
"if you stay there long enough,
that bullet will be fired."

00:40:54.230 --> 00:40:57.560
"GILBERT: Bill saw a lot of
his friends being laid off,"

00:40:57.560 --> 00:40:59.530
and he worried about
what would happen to him.

00:40:59.530 --> 00:41:01.900
"But when the axe finally fell,"

00:41:01.900 --> 00:41:05.100
Bill did something
a bit unusual.

00:41:05.100 --> 00:41:06.760
"Steph was on maternity leave,"

00:41:06.760 --> 00:41:08.860
and she planned to have a
sabbatical before going back

00:41:08.860 --> 00:41:10.960
"to work, so she was planning
on having six months."

00:41:10.960 --> 00:41:13.630
"I said, ""You know, I
dont think I want to..."

00:41:13.630 --> 00:41:15.900
"""just start pounding the
pavement, looking for a job."

00:41:15.900 --> 00:41:18.930
"Why don't... what do you
think if we buy an RV?"""

00:41:18.930 --> 00:41:20.830
(laughing)

00:41:20.830 --> 00:41:22.360
"And I said, ""I
think you're crazy."""

00:41:22.360 --> 00:41:23.700
"And his mom was living here,"

00:41:23.700 --> 00:41:25.560
"and she said, ""I
think you're crazy."""

00:41:25.560 --> 00:41:26.660
Yeah.

00:41:26.660 --> 00:41:28.530
Wasn't a well-received
idea at first.

00:41:28.530 --> 00:41:32.760
"I found a very cheap
Winnebago online,"

00:41:32.760 --> 00:41:34.460
spent the summer
together as a family

00:41:34.460 --> 00:41:36.300
driving around the country.

00:41:36.300 --> 00:41:38.000
Were just going to break
away for a little while.

00:41:38.000 --> 00:41:41.900
GILBERT: Why would you buy
an RV if you lost your job

00:41:41.900 --> 00:41:43.400
and had a new baby?

00:41:43.400 --> 00:41:46.900
"Well, research on
happiness suggests that
Bill and Stephanie"

00:41:46.900 --> 00:41:49.800
may have been spending their
money wisely by investing

00:41:49.800 --> 00:41:51.600
in a shared experience
rather material goods.

00:41:51.600 --> 00:41:53.160
O'CONNOR: It was great.

00:41:53.160 --> 00:41:54.500
You get up in the morning

00:41:54.500 --> 00:41:57.430
and you go out and
have lunch by a lake

00:41:57.430 --> 00:41:58.800
or you go swimming.

00:41:58.800 --> 00:42:00.560
It was just time together.

00:42:00.560 --> 00:42:02.200
There's just freedom.

00:42:02.200 --> 00:42:04.360
"You can just be driving
along and you see something,"

00:42:04.360 --> 00:42:06.360
"and you say, ""That
looks interesting;
let's stop there."""

00:42:06.360 --> 00:42:08.200
"""All right, let's
stop there."""

00:42:08.200 --> 00:42:12.360
"You know, we went and saw the
six-legged cow in Kansas."

00:42:12.360 --> 00:42:16.730
It was a once-in-a-lifetime
experience.

00:42:16.730 --> 00:42:18.160
STEPHANIE: I think it
really turned out to be

00:42:18.160 --> 00:42:22.200
one of the best things we
could have done for ourselves.

00:42:22.200 --> 00:42:24.430
"GILBERT: But no
vacation lasts forever,"

00:42:24.430 --> 00:42:26.660
"and when Bill and Stephanie
returned to New York,"

00:42:26.660 --> 00:42:28.830
Bills unemployment began to seem

00:42:28.830 --> 00:42:32.200
much less like an opportunity
and much more like a problem.

00:42:32.200 --> 00:42:36.830
OCONNOR: Coming back to
New York was not good.

00:42:36.830 --> 00:42:39.760
I was coming back
to play Mr. Mom

00:42:39.760 --> 00:42:47.430
"and look for a job that, you
know, doesn't seem to be there."

00:42:47.430 --> 00:42:49.760
OCONNOR: What time do you
have to go to work tomorrow?

00:42:49.760 --> 00:42:52.160
You're just working
in the office?

00:42:52.160 --> 00:42:53.860
STEPHANIE: Im working
in the office.

00:42:53.860 --> 00:42:56.030
"GILBERT: With their vacation
a rapidly vanishing memory,"

00:42:56.030 --> 00:42:58.530
Bill found himself
struggling to adjust to life

00:42:58.530 --> 00:43:00.600
as a stay-at-home father.

00:43:00.600 --> 00:43:03.130
What else do I have
to do this week?

00:43:03.130 --> 00:43:05.760
Itd be great if you can
get to the grocery store.

00:43:05.760 --> 00:43:18.030
Because were pretty limited in
what we have in the fridge.

00:43:18.030 --> 00:43:21.000
"Now we're going to shop, bud."

00:43:21.000 --> 00:43:25.700
"Is Tide really worth six
dollars more, Matty?"

00:43:25.700 --> 00:43:28.300
Your mothers using
generic right now.

00:43:28.300 --> 00:43:31.830
"This could cause
a disagreement, but
we're getting it."

00:43:31.830 --> 00:43:34.430
"These look identical, friend."

00:43:34.430 --> 00:43:36.630
Think you're going generic.

00:43:36.630 --> 00:43:41.760
"Congratulations, you've
just saved us $12."

00:43:41.760 --> 00:43:47.230
"OCONNOR: I hate
expensive grocery stores,
so I opt to go across"

00:43:47.230 --> 00:43:52.200
to New Jersey to Pathmark
or Shoprite or something.

00:43:52.200 --> 00:43:55.230
We get toilet paper... we
didnt get toilet paper yet.

00:43:55.230 --> 00:43:57.560
Goodness. (sighs)

00:43:57.560 --> 00:43:59.630
We have to reorganize.

00:43:59.630 --> 00:44:03.360
OCONNOR: Its bizarre
to have gone from a world
where I put on my headset

00:44:03.360 --> 00:44:07.260
in the morning and I had
150 phone lines and...

00:44:07.260 --> 00:44:10.360
"Im kind of lost without
that, without the dialogue,"

00:44:10.360 --> 00:44:12.130
without the interaction.

00:44:12.130 --> 00:44:15.030
"And then just the confusion
of, ""Where am I going?"""

00:44:15.030 --> 00:44:18.230
"I don't know, I have no idea."

00:44:18.230 --> 00:44:20.960
On your back.

00:44:20.960 --> 00:44:22.660
Smile.

00:44:22.660 --> 00:44:26.930
O'CONNOR: The challenging
thing... it's a full-time job.

00:44:26.930 --> 00:44:29.900
Ive opted for a full-time job.

00:44:29.900 --> 00:44:31.230
(baby coos)

00:44:31.230 --> 00:44:32.660
"Matty, whatcha doing?"

00:44:32.660 --> 00:44:35.130
"When you just want a moment,
you can't have a moment,"

00:44:35.130 --> 00:44:37.000
so that's exhausting.

00:44:37.000 --> 00:44:39.760
(dog panting)

00:44:39.760 --> 00:44:42.230
(baby crying)

00:44:42.230 --> 00:44:44.500
OCONNOR: I never saw
myself doing the job
Im doing right now.

00:44:44.500 --> 00:44:46.800
It's bizarre.

00:44:46.800 --> 00:44:49.500
"STEPHANIE: You could tell
when he had a successful day,"

00:44:49.500 --> 00:44:54.360
"when he had a good deal,
it was so fun for him."

00:44:54.360 --> 00:44:56.660
He loved what he did.

00:44:56.660 --> 00:44:58.230
"When he lost his job,"

00:44:58.230 --> 00:45:03.730
it seemed like he really
lost part of his identity.

00:45:03.730 --> 00:45:06.500
"O'CONNOR: You question,
you know, ""Why me?"

00:45:06.500 --> 00:45:09.760
"How could they
possibly pick me?"""

00:45:09.760 --> 00:45:14.330
"I still send instant messages
to the guy who I sat next to,"

00:45:14.330 --> 00:45:18.560
"like were chit-chatting,
you know, every day, so..."

00:45:18.560 --> 00:45:21.060
"The relationships
are still there,"

00:45:21.060 --> 00:45:24.630
but its like you got kicked
off the train or something.

00:45:24.630 --> 00:45:27.760
You gotta watch that thing
keep going down the tracks.

00:45:27.760 --> 00:45:29.760
"GILBERT: Bills
struggle isnt over yet,"

00:45:29.760 --> 00:45:32.800
and theres no telling
how long it will go on.

00:45:32.800 --> 00:45:36.030
"For now, one thing is clear:
Playing the role of Mr. Mom"

00:45:36.030 --> 00:45:40.100
doesn't seem to suit
him all that well.

00:45:40.100 --> 00:45:43.200
"Being unemployed obviously
makes us unhappy,"

00:45:43.200 --> 00:45:45.930
but the reasons arent
entirely financial.

00:45:45.930 --> 00:45:49.000
"When someone asks us
who we are, we often
tell them what we do,"

00:45:49.000 --> 00:45:51.660
because work is more
than a way to make money;

00:45:51.660 --> 00:45:53.360
it's a part of our identity.

00:45:53.360 --> 00:45:55.100
"Thats why when
we lose our jobs,"

00:45:55.100 --> 00:45:57.930
we lose a piece of ourselves.

00:45:57.930 --> 00:45:59.760
The same is true of illness.

00:45:59.760 --> 00:46:02.500
"Being sick makes us unhappy,"

00:46:02.500 --> 00:46:05.300
but the reasons are
not entirely medical.

00:46:05.300 --> 00:46:08.530
"Illness, like unemployment, can
tear a hole in our identities"

00:46:08.530 --> 00:46:12.260
and leave us wondering
who we really are.

00:46:12.260 --> 00:46:15.530
WOMAN: My hair was me.

00:46:15.530 --> 00:46:23.830
"My hair was red, full,
curly, shiny, long."

00:46:23.830 --> 00:46:27.400
So I was all hair.

00:46:27.400 --> 00:46:30.900
"It had a presence,
and I had a presence."

00:46:30.900 --> 00:46:34.160
GILBERT: Michele Gossett was
a 51-year-old single mother

00:46:34.160 --> 00:46:37.430
when she learned that
she had ovarian cancer.

00:46:37.430 --> 00:46:40.160
GOSSETT: Losing my hair
was probably one of the
most devastating things

00:46:40.160 --> 00:46:43.230
that happened to
me with my cancer.

00:46:43.230 --> 00:46:46.360
I lost my hair in one day...

00:46:46.360 --> 00:46:49.430
and I thought that
I lost my identity.

00:46:49.430 --> 00:46:55.730
"I thought I lost my
soul, I lost my strength."

00:46:55.730 --> 00:47:02.260
I actually have a different
hairstyle almost every day.

00:47:02.260 --> 00:47:10.160
"For instance, I'll wear my
pink wig when I feel playful."

00:47:10.160 --> 00:47:14.300
My red hair with the roots
I think looks very natural

00:47:14.300 --> 00:47:17.860
and I put that on to
kind of even me out

00:47:17.860 --> 00:47:21.800
but with a little edge.

00:47:21.800 --> 00:47:26.130
The brown ones... they more
or less resemble a hairstyle

00:47:26.130 --> 00:47:29.500
that I would possibly
adapt myself.

00:47:29.500 --> 00:47:32.100
And then I have little
short sassy ones.

00:47:32.100 --> 00:47:38.100
And those are fun
just for a change.

00:47:38.100 --> 00:47:40.560
Sometimes it's not easy.

00:47:40.560 --> 00:47:47.500
"Sometimes I'll get up and look
at the wigs and... ""Why?"""

00:47:47.500 --> 00:47:50.660
I realize I still have cancer.

00:47:50.660 --> 00:47:54.630
So sometimes it doesn't
really cut through that.

00:47:54.630 --> 00:48:00.730
(indistinct train
station announcement)

00:48:00.730 --> 00:48:04.930
I worry about my daughter.

00:48:04.930 --> 00:48:07.400
Natalie is absolutely
the apple of my eye.

00:48:07.400 --> 00:48:09.660
She is my pride and joy.

00:48:09.660 --> 00:48:13.730
And Natalie and I have been
through a lot together.

00:48:13.730 --> 00:48:16.860
"I was a nurse,"

00:48:16.860 --> 00:48:19.600
worked in critical care
for a number of years.

00:48:19.600 --> 00:48:22.000
"Oh, its so nice to see you."

00:48:22.000 --> 00:48:25.060
I decided to go to
anesthesia school.

00:48:25.060 --> 00:48:28.400
When I finished school I had
a promise of a wonderful job

00:48:28.400 --> 00:48:30.300
with a fabulous salary.

00:48:30.300 --> 00:48:32.660
I had a house on the water.

00:48:32.660 --> 00:48:38.130
My dreams were that Natalie
and I could live a secure life

00:48:38.130 --> 00:48:40.260
"in my future,"

00:48:40.260 --> 00:48:48.930
and that didn't materialize.

00:48:48.930 --> 00:48:53.160
"I was diagnosed two weeks
after my graduation,"

00:48:53.160 --> 00:48:56.300
and I'm on
chemotherapy right now.

00:48:56.300 --> 00:49:00.100
My fears with my illness lie

00:49:00.100 --> 00:49:03.760
in that Natalie might
not have her mother.

00:49:03.760 --> 00:49:08.560
Natalie is as important
to me as myself.

00:49:08.560 --> 00:49:10.830
"So, how are you feeling?"

00:49:10.830 --> 00:49:12.930
"Well, I'm really tired."

00:49:12.930 --> 00:49:15.700
"It went well,
everything went great."

00:49:15.700 --> 00:49:19.360
GILBERT: Michele is struggling
with her fear and anxiety.

00:49:19.360 --> 00:49:21.060
"And like many others
in the same situation,"

00:49:21.060 --> 00:49:24.530
shes turning to the self-help
industry for advice.

00:49:24.530 --> 00:49:30.530
GOSSETT: Im just looking for
secrets to find inner peace.

00:49:30.530 --> 00:49:33.400
I'm using aromatherapy.

00:49:33.400 --> 00:49:37.130
"Aromatherapy baths,
aromatherapy around my home."

00:49:37.130 --> 00:49:42.100
Im living and eating
more organic food.

00:49:42.100 --> 00:49:46.160
Ive found that I have been
reading a lot of self-help books

00:49:46.160 --> 00:49:51.830
"lately, inspirational readings,
inspirational writers."

00:49:51.830 --> 00:49:54.830
"William Dyer,
Marianne Williamson,"

00:49:54.830 --> 00:49:57.330
"Louise Hay, different authors."

00:49:57.330 --> 00:50:00.300
"""You can heal
yourself"" type things."

00:50:00.300 --> 00:50:01.960
"And I think thats
what we all want,"

00:50:01.960 --> 00:50:03.130
we want to enjoy life.

00:50:03.130 --> 00:50:05.530
(cheers and applause)

00:50:05.530 --> 00:50:08.960
GOSSETT: And its so pressing
for me to try and find these

00:50:08.960 --> 00:50:10.930
because I feel Im
reaching a desperation

00:50:10.930 --> 00:50:12.960
to find the meaning of life.

00:50:12.960 --> 00:50:15.360
GILBERT: Michele is
one of the thousands

00:50:15.360 --> 00:50:17.660
who attended Louise
Hays conference.

00:50:17.660 --> 00:50:20.100
GOSSETT: What I wanted to gain
from going to the conference

00:50:20.100 --> 00:50:23.860
"was keys, tricks, guidance."

00:50:23.860 --> 00:50:26.330
"""The healing has
begun. Life loves you."""

00:50:26.330 --> 00:50:28.000
Thank you so much.

00:50:28.000 --> 00:50:30.900
"GILBERT: As a trained nurse,
she isnt quite ready to believe"

00:50:30.900 --> 00:50:33.900
"that cancer can be cured
by aromatherapy, crystals,"

00:50:33.900 --> 00:50:35.660
or positive thinking.

00:50:35.660 --> 00:50:37.860
GOSSETT: Im not willing
to give up my chemotherapy

00:50:37.860 --> 00:50:39.960
"for alternative therapies,"

00:50:39.960 --> 00:50:44.230
because Ive seen tragic
outcomes from that.

00:50:44.230 --> 00:50:47.100
"They said, ""I'm just
going to have a vegan diet"

00:50:47.100 --> 00:50:48.930
"""and Im gonna
think positively,"

00:50:48.930 --> 00:50:51.630
"""and thats how Im gonna
live out the rest of my life"

00:50:51.630 --> 00:50:53.660
"because this will cure me."""

00:50:53.660 --> 00:50:56.530
"And their cancer just
metastasized to their brain,"

00:50:56.530 --> 00:50:59.100
"their bone, their lungs,
and they were done."

00:50:59.100 --> 00:51:02.260
I'm not ready to
take that chance.

00:51:02.260 --> 00:51:03.760
"When I put myself in
your position, I think,"

00:51:03.760 --> 00:51:05.600
"""If somebody told me that
the reason I have cancer"

00:51:05.600 --> 00:51:07.800
"""is that I had the
wrong thoughts,"""

00:51:07.800 --> 00:51:09.930
"is there a part of you that
thinks, ""Give me a break""?"

00:51:09.930 --> 00:51:11.700
I've-I've thought about it.

00:51:11.700 --> 00:51:15.630
"Because I said, ""Okay, if its
dis-ease in my body somewhere"

00:51:15.630 --> 00:51:17.600
"""and it manifests
in my cancer,"

00:51:17.600 --> 00:51:21.100
"""is it something from my
childhood? Is it an anger?"

00:51:21.100 --> 00:51:22.860
"Is it someone I
won't forgive?"""

00:51:22.860 --> 00:51:25.630
"That could lead to, I would
think, maybe, a stomach ulcer."

00:51:25.630 --> 00:51:27.700
Would it lead to cancer?

00:51:27.700 --> 00:51:29.460
Gynecological cancer?

00:51:29.460 --> 00:51:30.630
I dont know.

00:51:30.630 --> 00:51:36.900
I dont know about that.

00:51:36.900 --> 00:51:39.260
"GILBERT: There is, of course,
no scientific evidence"

00:51:39.260 --> 00:51:42.260
to suggest that self-help
techniques can cure cancer

00:51:42.260 --> 00:51:45.230
or any serious physical malady.

00:51:45.230 --> 00:51:47.200
But what about other
kinds of problems--

00:51:47.200 --> 00:51:51.030
"problems like addiction, or
depression, or marital strife?"

00:51:51.030 --> 00:51:54.430
"For many people, self-help
appears to be a simple"

00:51:54.430 --> 00:51:58.030
and inexpensive alternative
to therapy or counseling.

00:51:58.030 --> 00:52:01.360
But do these techniques
actually work?

00:52:01.360 --> 00:52:04.930
"Well, Im a big proponent
of decent self-help."

00:52:04.930 --> 00:52:06.960
"Here we go, Dan, self-help."

00:52:06.960 --> 00:52:09.160
"GILBERT: Over the
last 20 years,"

00:52:09.160 --> 00:52:11.160
psychology professor
John Norcross

00:52:11.160 --> 00:52:14.960
"has directed a systematic study
of the self-help industry,"

00:52:14.960 --> 00:52:17.730
examining over a thousand
different books and programs.

00:52:17.730 --> 00:52:21.000
NORCROSS: We should
be cheering about the
proliferation of self-help.

00:52:21.000 --> 00:52:26.400
Approximately 75% of those
who successfully changed

00:52:26.400 --> 00:52:28.930
a behavior or relationship
have done so on their own

00:52:28.930 --> 00:52:30.500
without professional treatment.

00:52:30.500 --> 00:52:34.560
Self-help is the major pathway
to how most of us grow.

00:52:34.560 --> 00:52:36.630
At the same time there
are inherent limitations

00:52:36.630 --> 00:52:38.000
"to self-help,"

00:52:38.000 --> 00:52:40.660
and not all the stuff out
there is particularly good.

00:52:40.660 --> 00:52:42.630
Great book.

00:52:42.630 --> 00:52:45.860
And then a not-so-great book.

00:52:45.860 --> 00:52:48.360
GILBERT: Norcross worries
that whats advertised
as expert advice...

00:52:48.360 --> 00:52:51.330
All on the same shelf.

00:52:51.330 --> 00:52:52.900
"Yes, right next to each other."

00:52:52.900 --> 00:52:55.760
GILBERT: ...is often nothing
more than untested opinion.

00:52:55.760 --> 00:52:59.430
More than 95% of all
self-help books are published

00:52:59.430 --> 00:53:01.800
without any scientific research

00:53:01.800 --> 00:53:05.160
attesting to their
effectiveness or safety.

00:53:05.160 --> 00:53:10.600
And we estimate more than 99%
of the Internet self-help sites

00:53:10.600 --> 00:53:13.230
are launched without
any scientific research

00:53:13.230 --> 00:53:14.900
attesting to their value.

00:53:14.900 --> 00:53:18.660
"So youre not just saying that
some self-help is worthless,"

00:53:18.660 --> 00:53:20.460
youre saying that some of
its positively dangerous.

00:53:20.460 --> 00:53:24.030
"Without any regulation and
without scientific research,"

00:53:24.030 --> 00:53:25.400
"its a ""buyer beware"""

00:53:25.400 --> 00:53:28.300
and theyre not sure
what theyre getting.

00:53:28.300 --> 00:53:30.700
I remember someone
once comparing it

00:53:30.700 --> 00:53:33.060
to taking a two-year-old
toddler on a walk.

00:53:33.060 --> 00:53:34.760
"As youre walking around,"

00:53:34.760 --> 00:53:36.300
the toddler will
occasionally pick up

00:53:36.300 --> 00:53:38.400
perhaps something of value but
mostly theyre just picking up

00:53:38.400 --> 00:53:41.960
dirt and germs.

00:53:41.960 --> 00:53:45.930
GILBERT: Self-help offers
quick and easy solutions
to complex problems.

00:53:45.930 --> 00:53:49.160
Thats why its so appealing
and so profitable

00:53:49.160 --> 00:53:50.960
from the corners of
your local bookstore

00:53:50.960 --> 00:53:54.000
to the media capitals
of the world.

00:53:54.000 --> 00:53:56.130
"And yet, despite
the proliferation"

00:53:56.130 --> 00:53:57.960
"of self-proclaimed experts,"

00:53:57.960 --> 00:53:59.960
huge numbers of Americans
get psychological advice

00:53:59.960 --> 00:54:02.700
from just one man.

00:54:02.700 --> 00:54:03.830
"GILBERT: So, who brought who?"

00:54:03.830 --> 00:54:06.200
WOMAN: It's a ritual.

00:54:06.200 --> 00:54:09.100
"At 5:00, when he comes
on in our area, is
when the TV goes on."

00:54:09.100 --> 00:54:10.600
"We see Dr. Phil,
then have dinner."

00:54:10.600 --> 00:54:12.130
I like Dr. Phil.

00:54:12.130 --> 00:54:14.700
I like his whole family; you
just feel like a part of it.

00:54:14.700 --> 00:54:16.660
How long have you been
watching Dr. Phil?

00:54:16.660 --> 00:54:19.360
"Well, when he was first
on Oprah years ago,"

00:54:19.360 --> 00:54:21.130
I wouldnt watch it on that day

00:54:21.130 --> 00:54:22.960
because I thought
he was so mean.

00:54:22.960 --> 00:54:25.660
"I was like, ""He's
so hard on people."""

00:54:25.660 --> 00:54:27.230
"I mean, now I think thats
what I like about him,"

00:54:27.230 --> 00:54:29.300
"is that hes just very direct,"

00:54:29.300 --> 00:54:30.800
"just the way he does, like,"

00:54:30.800 --> 00:54:32.760
"the ""Hows it workin for
ya?"" thing, you know?"

00:54:32.760 --> 00:54:36.200
"""If it's not working, stop
doing it,"" so I like that."

00:54:36.200 --> 00:54:38.100
"Its like the type of
family that I come from,"

00:54:38.100 --> 00:54:39.430
you don't talk
about your issues.

00:54:39.430 --> 00:54:42.830
"You just kind of, you know,
push it under the rug"

00:54:42.830 --> 00:54:47.000
"and you dont repeat
it, because there's a
lot of shame involved."

00:54:47.000 --> 00:54:48.930
"And so Dr. Phil,
he brings it out."

00:54:48.930 --> 00:54:52.260
Its almost like an accelerated
way to fix your problem.

00:54:52.260 --> 00:54:54.830
"Because you can beat
around the bush for years,"

00:54:54.830 --> 00:54:57.630
"or you can just, you know,
nip it in the bud right then."

00:54:57.630 --> 00:55:12.900
(audience cheers)

00:55:12.900 --> 00:55:14.960
DR. PHIL: And so your
goal is to inflict pain.

00:55:14.960 --> 00:55:17.300
"WOMAN: It becomes my goal,"

00:55:17.300 --> 00:55:19.200
but I dont think that
when we start fighting

00:55:19.200 --> 00:55:20.700
"that thats my goal,"

00:55:20.700 --> 00:55:22.330
but it becomes my
goal during the fight.

00:55:22.330 --> 00:55:24.100
"Are you proud of
that? No, Im not."

00:55:24.100 --> 00:55:25.630
"No, come on, be
serious about it."

00:55:25.630 --> 00:55:27.960
"Im not, Im not. Dont
give me that crap."

00:55:27.960 --> 00:55:30.960
GILBERT: Dr. Phil is
clearly a showman.

00:55:30.960 --> 00:55:33.130
But hes also a
trained psychologist

00:55:33.130 --> 00:55:35.800
who respects
scientific evidence.

00:55:35.800 --> 00:55:38.630
DR. PHIL: I have a staff of
over 300 people on this show

00:55:38.630 --> 00:55:41.630
and many of them
are researchers.

00:55:41.630 --> 00:55:44.060
"So theyll get into
the psych abstracts,"

00:55:44.060 --> 00:55:47.460
"the medical abstracts, the
sociological literature,"

00:55:47.460 --> 00:55:53.160
and pull out those cutting-edge
overviews of everything

00:55:53.160 --> 00:55:56.160
that is at least the
current understanding.

00:55:56.160 --> 00:56:00.400
"In my journey through the
land of psychotherapy,"

00:56:00.400 --> 00:56:04.100
"looking into self-help,
meeting therapists,"

00:56:04.100 --> 00:56:06.000
going to self-help conferences

00:56:06.000 --> 00:56:09.060
I found that theres huge
distinctions to be made

00:56:09.060 --> 00:56:11.960
between different
sources of help.

00:56:11.960 --> 00:56:14.300
I think science
informs practice.

00:56:14.300 --> 00:56:16.360
I think practice
informs science.

00:56:16.360 --> 00:56:19.300
"And if you dont
have that exchange,"

00:56:19.300 --> 00:56:22.830
I think youre gonna miss some
really important elements.

00:56:22.830 --> 00:56:25.930
"But Im not one of those
people that thinks, you know,"

00:56:25.930 --> 00:56:28.030
you can think your
way to illness

00:56:28.030 --> 00:56:29.800
or you can think
your way to health.

00:56:29.800 --> 00:56:32.700
I think its a
multifaceted aspect.

00:56:32.700 --> 00:56:36.330
"GILBERT: Dr. Phil is in
the helping business,"

00:56:36.330 --> 00:56:38.930
but hes also in the
entertainment business...

00:56:38.930 --> 00:56:41.900
Im going to tell them and
you how to fight fair.

00:56:41.900 --> 00:56:44.830
GILBERT: ...and he knows what
it takes to keep ratings high.

00:56:44.830 --> 00:56:46.860
Ill tell him that
he sucks in bed;

00:56:46.860 --> 00:56:49.460
its just one more
way to hurt him.

00:56:49.460 --> 00:56:52.160
"GILBERT: In the end,
a television show
is no substitute"

00:56:52.160 --> 00:56:53.460
for professional help...

00:56:53.460 --> 00:56:55.400
"A lot of couples go through
this kind of thing,"

00:56:55.400 --> 00:56:56.830
which is why Im talking to yall.

00:56:56.830 --> 00:56:58.930
GILBERT: ...something Dr.
Phil appears to recognize.

00:56:58.930 --> 00:57:00.760
"DR. Phil: A lot of people
at home are thinking,"

00:57:00.760 --> 00:57:02.930
"""Whew, my marriage isnt as
bad as I thought it was."""

00:57:02.930 --> 00:57:04.300
GILBERT: People watch your show

00:57:04.300 --> 00:57:05.930
"hoping to get
answers, and they do."

00:57:05.930 --> 00:57:08.560
"Some people watch your show
hoping to get all the answers,"

00:57:08.560 --> 00:57:09.860
"and, of course, they don't."

00:57:09.860 --> 00:57:11.700
"Dan, Ive never been
under the misconception"

00:57:11.700 --> 00:57:14.660
that were doing eight-minute
cures on the Dr. Phil show.

00:57:14.660 --> 00:57:19.030
What we do try and do is
give people a wake-up call.

00:57:19.030 --> 00:57:22.930
"To get themselves thinking, to
get themselves considering."

00:57:22.930 --> 00:57:25.230
But this is just that--
its a beginning place.

00:57:25.230 --> 00:57:30.560
"It should open a dialogue, it
should open a thought process."

00:57:30.560 --> 00:57:33.530
It should cause them to maybe
write down five questions

00:57:33.530 --> 00:57:36.200
to ask their therapist or their
doctor the next time they go in

00:57:36.200 --> 00:57:39.600
"and see em, or to discuss
with their spouse that night."

00:57:39.600 --> 00:57:41.200
Then that's a great thing.

00:57:41.200 --> 00:57:42.760
"If they take it beyond that,"

00:57:42.760 --> 00:57:47.260
"I think theyre trying to do
too much with the platform,"

00:57:47.260 --> 00:57:50.630
too much with the venue.

00:57:50.630 --> 00:57:52.900
GILBERT: Dr. Phil is
undoubtedly helping some people

00:57:52.900 --> 00:57:55.630
"by reducing the
stigma of therapy,"

00:57:55.630 --> 00:58:01.460
but dealing with life's
problems is hard work.

00:58:01.460 --> 00:58:05.600
"Self-help programs often focus
on changing how we think,"

00:58:05.600 --> 00:58:07.800
but research suggests that
it can be more effective

00:58:07.800 --> 00:58:10.100
to change how we behave.

00:58:10.100 --> 00:58:12.230
And one program in particular
has a track record

00:58:12.230 --> 00:58:14.300
of doing just that.

00:58:14.300 --> 00:58:17.200
"MAN: I had a
perfect childhood,"

00:58:17.200 --> 00:58:19.560
two parents who loved me and
loved me unconditionally;

00:58:19.560 --> 00:58:21.530
I lacked for nothing.

00:58:21.530 --> 00:58:25.060
"GILBERT: William Cope
Moyers, son of veteran
journalist Bill Moyers,"

00:58:25.060 --> 00:58:27.000
found out at a young age

00:58:27.000 --> 00:58:29.930
that all the family support
in the world wasn't enough.

00:58:29.930 --> 00:58:31.860
MOYERS: There was something
going on inside of me

00:58:31.860 --> 00:58:34.260
that wasnt satisfied

00:58:34.260 --> 00:58:36.230
by all of those external factors

00:58:36.230 --> 00:58:42.930
that would typically define
happiness or success.

00:58:42.930 --> 00:58:46.300
I was struggling with
the sense of purpose

00:58:46.300 --> 00:58:48.060
and the sense that I
wasn't good enough.

00:58:48.060 --> 00:58:51.460
I discovered the solution
to this hole in the soul.

00:58:51.460 --> 00:58:56.130
I could medicate it in a way
that required me only to use

00:58:56.130 --> 00:58:57.730
mood- and mind-altering
substances.

00:58:57.730 --> 00:59:01.200
I didn't have to try so
hard anymore to be happy.

00:59:01.200 --> 00:59:04.100
I didn't have to try so
hard anymore to be perfect.

00:59:04.100 --> 00:59:05.630
I could just get high.

00:59:05.630 --> 00:59:08.660
Taking drugs and drinking
probably became a problem

00:59:08.660 --> 00:59:10.230
from the moment I did them.

00:59:10.230 --> 00:59:12.960
"And Im convinced that once
I took a drink or a drug,"

00:59:12.960 --> 00:59:14.460
I was off to the races.

00:59:14.460 --> 00:59:17.400
"GILBERT: By the time
he was in his 20s,"

00:59:17.400 --> 00:59:20.630
Moyers addiction had
consumed his life.

00:59:20.630 --> 00:59:22.400
MOYERS: My fix
was crack cocaine.

00:59:22.400 --> 00:59:26.460
So I was using...
thousand dollars a week?

00:59:26.460 --> 00:59:27.960
"You know, the
money didnt matter."

00:59:27.960 --> 00:59:29.430
"I mean, it did, but it didn't."

00:59:29.430 --> 00:59:30.960
I was doing anything
to get high.

00:59:30.960 --> 00:59:32.830
My problem wasnt having
money in my pocket;

00:59:32.830 --> 00:59:34.200
I had money in my pocket.

00:59:34.200 --> 00:59:35.530
My problem was
finding my connection.

00:59:35.530 --> 00:59:40.900
"My bottom was on the morning
of October 12 of 1994,"

00:59:40.900 --> 00:59:43.600
"when, in a full-blown
relapse from my addiction,"

00:59:43.600 --> 00:59:45.860
"I was in a crack house
in Atlanta, Georgia,"

00:59:45.860 --> 00:59:51.330
"and this simple question popped
into my head: ""Now what?"""

00:59:51.330 --> 00:59:55.200
"And for the first time in my
life, I did not have an answer."

00:59:55.200 --> 00:59:57.400
"Its a simple
question, ""Now what?"

00:59:57.400 --> 00:59:59.060
"Now what am I gonna do?"""

00:59:59.060 --> 01:00:01.360
I didn't have the answer.

01:00:01.360 --> 01:00:05.260
GILBERT: The key
to his recovery?

01:00:05.260 --> 01:00:08.400
"Moyers joined the worlds
best-known self-help program,"

01:00:08.400 --> 01:00:10.400
Alcoholics Anonymous.

01:00:10.400 --> 01:00:14.860
"AA is a free, peer-based
support group that
offers daily meetings"

01:00:14.860 --> 01:00:19.000
in just about every city
and town in the nation.

01:00:19.000 --> 01:00:20.960
NORCROSS: Theres
decades of research now

01:00:20.960 --> 01:00:25.100
"investigating the effectiveness
of 12-step groups,"

01:00:25.100 --> 01:00:27.730
"including AA, NA and so forth."

01:00:27.730 --> 01:00:30.460
And the research is
quite supportive.

01:00:30.460 --> 01:00:34.630
Regular participation is an
incredibly positive factor.

01:00:34.630 --> 01:00:38.830
"The key is that sense of
validation, of universality,"

01:00:38.830 --> 01:00:41.460
that were all in
this boat together.

01:00:41.460 --> 01:00:45.330
"MOYERS: I mean,
in AA we realize its
really pretty simple."

01:00:45.330 --> 01:00:48.830
This isn't rocket science.

01:00:48.830 --> 01:00:50.800
It's about togetherness.

01:00:50.800 --> 01:00:52.460
"It's about ""we."""

01:00:52.460 --> 01:00:54.730
Its about realizing that
we dont have to go through

01:00:54.730 --> 01:00:57.300
lifes highs and lows
all by ourselves.

01:00:57.300 --> 01:00:59.300
"KEITH HUMPHREYS: If Im an
alcoholic, I have to decide,"

01:00:59.300 --> 01:01:00.700
"""Am I going to drink?"""

01:01:00.700 --> 01:01:03.230
"I can go to the bar, where
it would be harder for me."

01:01:03.230 --> 01:01:04.500
I can go to an AA meeting.

01:01:04.500 --> 01:01:07.530
I can seek out friends who
will help me in my recovery;

01:01:07.530 --> 01:01:10.100
I can seek out friends who will
ask me to go out for a beer.

01:01:10.100 --> 01:01:12.200
"GILBERT: Keith Humphreys,"

01:01:12.200 --> 01:01:14.830
"a psychiatry professor
at Stanford University,"

01:01:14.830 --> 01:01:17.960
has studied AA
for over 15 years.

01:01:17.960 --> 01:01:20.360
Hes identified social support--

01:01:20.360 --> 01:01:23.500
or what the folks in
AA call fellowship--

01:01:23.500 --> 01:01:25.660
as being the key to its success.

01:01:25.660 --> 01:01:26.830
"In my career, Ive studied"

01:01:26.830 --> 01:01:29.830
"a very broad range of
treatments for addiction,"

01:01:29.830 --> 01:01:32.260
and there are many
different things that work.

01:01:32.260 --> 01:01:35.330
"Um, but none of them will
fully supplant, I think,"

01:01:35.330 --> 01:01:37.960
the power of a fellowship
that can really become

01:01:37.960 --> 01:01:40.660
a part of a persons life for
years and years and years.

01:01:40.660 --> 01:01:44.760
And AA has definitely
figured that out.

01:01:44.760 --> 01:01:47.060
MOYERS: Im in that
meeting with those people

01:01:47.060 --> 01:01:49.300
because theyre
exactly like I am.

01:01:49.300 --> 01:01:52.900
"And so Joe, who I may
know from ten years ago,"

01:01:52.900 --> 01:01:54.530
"stands up and says,
""My name is Joe"

01:01:54.530 --> 01:01:55.830
"""and Im coming back
after a relapse."

01:01:55.830 --> 01:01:57.030
"I got six days."""

01:01:57.030 --> 01:01:59.430
"I go, ""Oh yeah, that's
what this is all about."""

01:01:59.430 --> 01:02:01.900
And then an old-timer gets
up and shares something

01:02:01.900 --> 01:02:03.730
"on one of the
steps and he says,"

01:02:03.730 --> 01:02:06.000
"""My name is Bob and Ive
been sober for 40 years,"""

01:02:06.000 --> 01:02:08.330
"and I say, ""Ah yes, that's
what this is all about."""

01:02:08.330 --> 01:02:11.130
"HUMPHREYS: AA creates
many, many opportunities"

01:02:11.130 --> 01:02:13.000
for people to be
helpful to others--

01:02:13.000 --> 01:02:16.360
bring in the chairs
and set up the coffee--

01:02:16.360 --> 01:02:18.630
but in most cases it's
more involved than that:

01:02:18.630 --> 01:02:21.930
leading a meeting or
sponsoring other people

01:02:21.930 --> 01:02:24.130
to help them through
the recovery process.

01:02:24.130 --> 01:02:26.430
And what research has shown

01:02:26.430 --> 01:02:28.130
"is that the people who
sponsor other members,"

01:02:28.130 --> 01:02:30.130
the people who
hold their hand out

01:02:30.130 --> 01:02:32.130
and support new
members in recovery

01:02:32.130 --> 01:02:34.360
are more likely to
stay sober themselves.

01:02:34.360 --> 01:02:37.130
"So thats, I think, part
of the genius of AA,"

01:02:37.130 --> 01:02:41.160
"to recognize that to get help,
one also needs to give it away."

01:02:41.160 --> 01:02:44.830
GILBERT: Moyers is now the
executive director of advocacy

01:02:44.830 --> 01:02:47.900
"at Hazelden, a drug and
alcohol treatment center"

01:02:47.900 --> 01:02:51.330
that employs
principles based on AA.

01:02:51.330 --> 01:02:54.330
"MOYERS: I used to
always believe that when
Im on my death bed,"

01:02:54.330 --> 01:02:56.100
"Ill probably get
high one more time,"

01:02:56.100 --> 01:02:57.930
just to go through
it one more time.

01:02:57.930 --> 01:02:59.260
"No, I want to die sober."

01:02:59.260 --> 01:03:01.860
There is no cure
for my alcoholism.

01:03:01.860 --> 01:03:05.200
There is a solution and
the solution is recovery.

01:03:05.200 --> 01:03:10.460
Recovery includes
going to meetings.

01:03:10.460 --> 01:03:12.660
GILBERT: AA meetings
often end with a prayer:

01:03:12.660 --> 01:03:14.230
"""God grant me the serenity"

01:03:14.230 --> 01:03:15.960
"""to accept the things
I cannot change,"

01:03:15.960 --> 01:03:18.300
"""the courage to
change the things I can"

01:03:18.300 --> 01:03:20.300
"and the wisdom to
know the difference."""

01:03:20.300 --> 01:03:22.900
That wisdom is
critical for everyone.

01:03:22.900 --> 01:03:25.260
"And yet, knowing what
can and cant be changed"

01:03:25.260 --> 01:03:27.160
isnt always easy.

01:03:27.160 --> 01:03:29.500
Most of us find
it hard to accept

01:03:29.500 --> 01:03:31.030
that some of the
wrongs weve suffered

01:03:31.030 --> 01:03:34.300
simply can't be righted.

01:03:34.300 --> 01:03:36.530
STEPHEN ROWELL: Ive been
struggling with forgiveness

01:03:36.530 --> 01:03:38.630
for quite some time.

01:03:38.630 --> 01:03:40.830
"Eight years, to be exact."

01:03:40.830 --> 01:03:47.360
I had an accident
that changed my life.

01:03:47.360 --> 01:03:49.630
I was in New Orleans.

01:03:49.630 --> 01:03:53.860
It was the weekend of my
younger brother's wedding.

01:03:53.860 --> 01:03:58.660
And we were on a balcony at a
club and the railing gave way.

01:03:58.660 --> 01:04:03.630
"There was a gentleman to my
left, who started to go over."

01:04:03.630 --> 01:04:05.000
His natural reaction

01:04:05.000 --> 01:04:10.060
was to reach and grab
hold of something

01:04:10.060 --> 01:04:11.430
and what he grabbed was me.

01:04:11.430 --> 01:04:15.500
"And we went free-falling
all the way to the street,"

01:04:15.500 --> 01:04:18.700
which is about 30 feet below.

01:04:18.700 --> 01:04:21.760
I felt like I was going
to die that night.

01:04:21.760 --> 01:04:25.700
And it's still hard
to think about it.

01:04:25.700 --> 01:04:28.700
GILBERT: Stephen Rowell
continues to suffer
from nerve damage

01:04:28.700 --> 01:04:30.260
and debilitating seizures.

01:04:30.260 --> 01:04:32.260
But even worse is
the emotional toll

01:04:32.260 --> 01:04:34.260
that his accident has taken.

01:04:34.260 --> 01:04:36.430
ROWELL: Ive been
holding a lot of anger

01:04:36.430 --> 01:04:39.060
and just a lot of pretty
horrific emotions

01:04:39.060 --> 01:04:42.400
in regards to the club owner.

01:04:42.400 --> 01:04:46.430
"It seemed that, you
know, every time I felt
like I might be able"

01:04:46.430 --> 01:04:52.160
"to let go, I would
have a seizure."

01:04:52.160 --> 01:04:54.630
And I look back at
some of my journals.

01:04:54.630 --> 01:04:57.160
I was really angry about this.

01:04:57.160 --> 01:05:00.330
And relentlessly unforgiving.

01:05:00.330 --> 01:05:02.060
And it just kept
me in that place.

01:05:02.060 --> 01:05:04.330
It kept me sort of
trapped in that place.

01:05:04.330 --> 01:05:07.060
"FRED LUSKIN: And again, one
more time, breathe in fully."

01:05:07.060 --> 01:05:09.030
"GILBERT: At the suggestion
of his therapist,"

01:05:09.030 --> 01:05:11.160
Stephen has enrolled
in a forgiveness class

01:05:11.160 --> 01:05:12.530
"at Stanford University,"

01:05:12.530 --> 01:05:15.900
"a five-week program
designed to alleviate anger,"

01:05:15.900 --> 01:05:17.830
stress and depression.

01:05:17.830 --> 01:05:20.830
"This is a guided, educational
practice in forgiveness."

01:05:20.830 --> 01:05:25.630
I lead you through a
series of practices

01:05:25.630 --> 01:05:29.930
"that at the end, you
become less attached"

01:05:29.930 --> 01:05:31.800
to a certain negative
point of view

01:05:31.800 --> 01:05:33.800
about something thats
happened to you.

01:05:33.800 --> 01:05:36.160
Im going to ask a few
of you just to talk

01:05:36.160 --> 01:05:37.700
about what brings you here.

01:05:37.700 --> 01:05:39.330
How about you?

01:05:39.330 --> 01:05:42.230
"You know, Im being sued by
somebody whos, you know,"

01:05:42.230 --> 01:05:46.360
"I... there's no basis, I
mean, it's just painful."

01:05:46.360 --> 01:05:51.760
"A bad childhood, you know, had
somehow anchored, you know, me"

01:05:51.760 --> 01:05:53.260
into a pit of negativity.

01:05:53.260 --> 01:05:55.460
But Im getting to
the point where...

01:05:55.460 --> 01:05:59.000
LUSKIN: What I see is so often
people have become paralyzed

01:05:59.000 --> 01:06:00.560
"because their
anger hasnt worked,"

01:06:00.560 --> 01:06:03.060
they have no idea
what else is available

01:06:03.060 --> 01:06:06.400
and are stuck by something
thats not working.

01:06:06.400 --> 01:06:10.260
"Anger, over time,
becomes less helpful."

01:06:10.260 --> 01:06:11.660
It actually becomes crippling.

01:06:11.660 --> 01:06:13.660
ROWELL: And sometimes I cant

01:06:13.660 --> 01:06:14.730
get beyond.

01:06:14.730 --> 01:06:15.830
Thats right.

01:06:15.830 --> 01:06:17.200
...whats happened in the past.

01:06:17.200 --> 01:06:19.160
So what would forgiveness be?

01:06:19.160 --> 01:06:21.560
"Youre right, and
what would it mean"

01:06:21.560 --> 01:06:23.700
to forgive?

01:06:23.700 --> 01:06:25.160
"Well, for me it would
mean everything."

01:06:25.160 --> 01:06:26.900
Somebody else.

01:06:26.900 --> 01:06:30.230
GILBERT: Dr. Fred Luskin
created this program in 1999.

01:06:30.230 --> 01:06:33.660
"Since then, it's been
tested around the globe."

01:06:33.660 --> 01:06:35.700
"LUSKIN: We worked with people
from Northern Ireland,"

01:06:35.700 --> 01:06:37.060
from both sides
of that conflict.

01:06:37.060 --> 01:06:39.330
We have really good data
that it was helpful to them.

01:06:39.330 --> 01:06:41.400
"People would come,
some of whom..."

01:06:41.400 --> 01:06:43.730
"whose children had been
murdered decades ago,"

01:06:43.730 --> 01:06:45.400
and it was just
eating them alive.

01:06:45.400 --> 01:06:47.400
"And we taught them
things about forgiveness,"

01:06:47.400 --> 01:06:50.600
and we could show that it
made a significant difference.

01:06:50.600 --> 01:06:53.160
So what would be a
question out of that?

01:06:53.160 --> 01:06:56.260
"LUSKIN: They had reduced
depression, reduced anger,"

01:06:56.260 --> 01:06:59.300
"physical improvements, reduced
stress and more hopefulness."

01:06:59.300 --> 01:07:04.060
"LUSKIN: Does thinking
that someone doesnt
deserve compassion,"

01:07:04.060 --> 01:07:05.900
does that help
solve your problem?

01:07:05.900 --> 01:07:07.060
"No, it doesn't."

01:07:07.060 --> 01:07:08.430
Does thinking

01:07:08.430 --> 01:07:11.330
that someone doesnt
deserve compassion

01:07:11.330 --> 01:07:12.800
help you feel at peace?

01:07:12.800 --> 01:07:13.860
No.

01:07:13.860 --> 01:07:15.930
So why do you continue to do it?

01:07:15.930 --> 01:07:19.960
"GILBERT: In each class,
Luskin provides exercises
to help students see"

01:07:19.960 --> 01:07:22.600
"that they cant control
what happened to them,"

01:07:22.600 --> 01:07:24.730
but they can control
how they think about it.

01:07:24.730 --> 01:07:26.400
The idea is to get people to see

01:07:26.400 --> 01:07:29.460
"that even though their
anger is justified,"

01:07:29.460 --> 01:07:31.060
it isn't hurting
anyone but them.

01:07:31.060 --> 01:07:33.600
LUSKIN: So the theme
through all of this is:

01:07:33.600 --> 01:07:36.860
Is the way youre dealing
with it helpful to you?

01:07:36.860 --> 01:07:38.330
"If it is, keep it."

01:07:38.330 --> 01:07:39.560
"If it's not, change it."

01:07:39.560 --> 01:07:41.100
Try being more grateful.

01:07:41.100 --> 01:07:43.030
Try being more compassionate.

01:07:43.030 --> 01:07:44.900
Try telling a different story.

01:07:44.900 --> 01:07:48.300
Try arguing yourself out
of feeling so entitled.

01:07:48.300 --> 01:07:50.230
"Any one of those
things can work,"

01:07:50.230 --> 01:07:54.360
"but the first recognition is,
I may not be helping myself."

01:07:54.360 --> 01:07:59.400
"If you do the same old same
old, expect the same result."

01:07:59.400 --> 01:08:01.760
And don't blame
anybody else for that.

01:08:01.760 --> 01:08:05.530
Because we get something
out of being righteous.

01:08:05.530 --> 01:08:07.530
We get something.

01:08:07.530 --> 01:08:10.530
"It's a substitute
for happiness, but
we get something."

01:08:10.530 --> 01:08:12.660
ROWELL: Dr. Luskin
kind of provoked me.

01:08:12.660 --> 01:08:16.030
I actually left our second
class very frustrated

01:08:16.030 --> 01:08:18.630
because I disagreed with him.

01:08:18.630 --> 01:08:22.530
"But, you know, I went back"

01:08:22.530 --> 01:08:27.760
"and kind of really
thought about what he
was saying, and..."

01:08:27.760 --> 01:08:34.000
that's where I started
to see a shift.

01:08:34.000 --> 01:08:37.300
"You know, what is it about me?"

01:08:37.300 --> 01:08:40.200
"You know, asking myself,
what is it about me"

01:08:40.200 --> 01:08:44.700
that I can do to change things?

01:08:44.700 --> 01:08:47.230
I really felt sort
of a breakthrough

01:08:47.230 --> 01:08:49.130
"in taking the class,"

01:08:49.130 --> 01:08:51.560
that it was sort
of a turning point.

01:08:51.560 --> 01:08:54.130
"Following the course, I..."

01:08:54.130 --> 01:08:59.430
"I called my attorney and
said, ""Im ready to settle."

01:08:59.430 --> 01:09:02.000
"""Im ready to just
put this behind me"

01:09:02.000 --> 01:09:04.900
"and start moving forward."""

01:09:04.900 --> 01:09:08.230
I have reached a point
of forgiving this man.

01:09:08.230 --> 01:09:12.300
I feel like I can finally
join the living again.

01:09:12.300 --> 01:09:18.800
And I can't tell you how
incredibly uplifting that is.

01:09:18.800 --> 01:09:20.760
GILBERT: One way
to change your life

01:09:20.760 --> 01:09:24.230
is to identify your
weaknesses and fix them.

01:09:24.230 --> 01:09:26.730
"But recently, some
researchers have suggested"

01:09:26.730 --> 01:09:29.100
"that rather than worrying
about our weaknesses,"

01:09:29.100 --> 01:09:32.600
"we should instead learn to
capitalize on our strengths,"

01:09:32.600 --> 01:09:34.800
and theyre developing
programs to accomplish this--

01:09:34.800 --> 01:09:38.060
"programs that are
inspired by self-help,"

01:09:38.060 --> 01:09:40.460
but that are
grounded in science.

01:09:40.460 --> 01:09:44.000
"The question is, what
self-help actually works,"

01:09:44.000 --> 01:09:48.030
and what self-help is
false and doesn't work?

01:09:48.030 --> 01:09:51.600
GILBERT: Psychologist Martin
Seligman is a professor

01:09:51.600 --> 01:09:53.330
at the University
of Pennsylvania

01:09:53.330 --> 01:09:55.300
and one of the leaders
of a new movement

01:09:55.300 --> 01:09:57.860
he calls positive psychology.

01:09:57.860 --> 01:10:00.730
I realized that psychology
had been all about whining

01:10:00.730 --> 01:10:03.700
"and suffering and anxiety,
depression, victims,"

01:10:03.700 --> 01:10:05.660
"suicide, drug addiction,"

01:10:05.660 --> 01:10:08.630
"and I had spent 35 years
working on those things,"

01:10:08.630 --> 01:10:10.200
but that that was half-baked.

01:10:10.200 --> 01:10:11.730
"Were pretty good at misery,"

01:10:11.730 --> 01:10:15.300
but what we werent good at was
what made life worth living.

01:10:15.300 --> 01:10:18.430
GILBERT: What distinguishes
positive psychology

01:10:18.430 --> 01:10:20.230
from any other
kind of self-help?

01:10:20.230 --> 01:10:23.730
"According to Seligman, it isn't
the message, but the method."

01:10:23.730 --> 01:10:26.800
"We do random-assignment,
placebo-controlled studies"

01:10:26.800 --> 01:10:29.730
and ask: does that make people
happier six months later

01:10:29.730 --> 01:10:31.100
and less depressed?

01:10:31.100 --> 01:10:35.360
So this is an empirically
based endeavor

01:10:35.360 --> 01:10:38.060
and a scientifically
based endeavor.

01:10:38.060 --> 01:10:41.960
GILBERT: Positive psychology
has gotten a lot of attention

01:10:41.960 --> 01:10:45.260
and its programs are now being
implemented all over the world

01:10:45.260 --> 01:10:48.800
"in businesses, in hospitals,
and even in the military."

01:10:48.800 --> 01:10:51.460
"At West Point, the
U.S. Army is hoping"

01:10:51.460 --> 01:10:53.300
that positive
psychology training

01:10:53.300 --> 01:10:54.800
will enhance leadership skills

01:10:54.800 --> 01:10:58.600
and make officers more resilient
in the face of battle.

01:10:58.600 --> 01:11:00.900
COLONEL PAT SWEENEY: The
graduates from West Point know

01:11:00.900 --> 01:11:02.230
"that theyre going out,"

01:11:02.230 --> 01:11:04.330
and theyre going to lead
men and women in combat.

01:11:04.330 --> 01:11:08.060
"And in ten to 12 months, theyll
report to their first unit,"

01:11:08.060 --> 01:11:10.760
"and, you know, depending on
their combat deployment cycle,"

01:11:10.760 --> 01:11:13.830
"they may be reporting straight
into Iraq or Afghanistan,"

01:11:13.830 --> 01:11:17.900
and theyll be responsible for
the lives of 45 men and women.

01:11:17.900 --> 01:11:19.700
"If you were the commander
of a lost battalion,"

01:11:19.700 --> 01:11:22.460
"in combat, in dire situation,"

01:11:22.460 --> 01:11:25.060
what character strengths
did you rely on

01:11:25.060 --> 01:11:27.430
that were important for
leadership in combat?

01:11:27.430 --> 01:11:28.960
"WOMAN: Everyone always thinks
of physical leadership,"

01:11:28.960 --> 01:11:30.600
but in this situation

01:11:30.600 --> 01:11:33.130
its that mental leadership
that you were talking about.

01:11:33.130 --> 01:11:35.400
I think of the
optimism and the hope

01:11:35.400 --> 01:11:37.430
that he is providing for them.

01:11:37.430 --> 01:11:38.930
"If you know what
youre good at,"

01:11:38.930 --> 01:11:40.960
you can be mindful
of those skills

01:11:40.960 --> 01:11:42.630
and then use them
when you need them.

01:11:42.630 --> 01:11:45.330
And I think that's what
this course is all about.

01:11:45.330 --> 01:11:48.660
"GILBERT: Psychologist
Chris Peterson, a
colleague of Seligmans,"

01:11:48.660 --> 01:11:51.300
has helped create this new
program for West Point.

01:11:51.300 --> 01:11:54.100
PETERSON: What we have
found in our research
over the past decade

01:11:54.100 --> 01:11:56.260
"is that you cant cultivate
the whole of character,"

01:11:56.260 --> 01:11:58.130
but you can certainly
cultivate its components.

01:11:58.130 --> 01:12:01.000
Right-- youre 100% correct.

01:12:01.000 --> 01:12:03.730
SWEENEY: The cadets really
like positive psychology

01:12:03.730 --> 01:12:06.100
"because instead of
focusing on weaknesses,"

01:12:06.100 --> 01:12:09.900
"what it is, is its a
focus on your strengths,"

01:12:09.900 --> 01:12:12.800
"and certain strengths may
be at different levels,"

01:12:12.800 --> 01:12:14.260
"but what were doing is saying,"

01:12:14.260 --> 01:12:16.960
"""Hey, lets take that strength
and lets build on it."""

01:12:16.960 --> 01:12:20.460
GILBERT: Petersons programs
revolve around the idea

01:12:20.460 --> 01:12:22.760
"that if you want to
develop your character,"

01:12:22.760 --> 01:12:24.260
you have to identify
your strengths

01:12:24.260 --> 01:12:26.900
and use them over
and over again.

01:12:26.900 --> 01:12:31.600
PETERSON: Most of the
interventions that have
been created to date

01:12:31.600 --> 01:12:33.060
are based on a
very simple premise

01:12:33.060 --> 01:12:34.730
that you are what you do.

01:12:34.730 --> 01:12:36.730
"And if you do more
of these things,"

01:12:36.730 --> 01:12:39.830
then youll be more of
whatever they represent.

01:12:39.830 --> 01:12:42.830
"So, how frequently
are you kind?"

01:12:42.830 --> 01:12:45.330
How often are you a leader?

01:12:45.330 --> 01:12:48.200
You start to keep track of that

01:12:48.200 --> 01:12:51.800
and then you start to
try to increase it.

01:12:51.800 --> 01:12:53.560
"And youre measuring
it all along,"

01:12:53.560 --> 01:12:58.000
so you can see your progress.

01:12:58.000 --> 01:12:59.900
GILBERT: West Point
is now testing

01:12:59.900 --> 01:13:01.830
the effectiveness of
Petersons programs

01:13:01.830 --> 01:13:03.530
and the outcome is uncertain.

01:13:03.530 --> 01:13:05.530
"Nonetheless, the
Army is creating"

01:13:05.530 --> 01:13:08.560
a positive psychology training
course that will be required

01:13:08.560 --> 01:13:13.200
for all its soldiers.

01:13:13.200 --> 01:13:16.900
And positive psychology is
also being used by civilians

01:13:16.900 --> 01:13:18.130
like Bill OConnor.

01:13:18.130 --> 01:13:21.560
"Yeah, it hasn't been a
good couple of weeks."

01:13:21.560 --> 01:13:25.630
"GILBERT: Bill still
faces a bad economy, with
no jobs and no prospects."

01:13:25.630 --> 01:13:28.700
How do you focus on doing
a financial job search

01:13:28.700 --> 01:13:33.430
when you can see the whole
system is just crashing?

01:13:33.430 --> 01:13:36.260
"How do you call up a guy
and say, ""Hey, you know,"

01:13:36.260 --> 01:13:38.630
"you have any idea
who's hiring today?"""

01:13:38.630 --> 01:13:42.500
"You sound like an
idiot, so its..."

01:13:42.500 --> 01:13:46.300
"Yeah, thats going
nowhere, I mean, its..."

01:13:46.300 --> 01:13:48.260
"GILBERT: With his
situation growing worse,"

01:13:48.260 --> 01:13:51.830
Bills sister-in-law
suggested that he get help

01:13:51.830 --> 01:13:53.460
from positive psychology
coach Senia Maymin.

01:13:53.460 --> 01:13:54.800
So what Ill give you

01:13:54.800 --> 01:13:58.000
over the course of our
coaching are tools.

01:13:58.000 --> 01:13:59.760
"So literally, hammer,
screwdriver..."

01:13:59.760 --> 01:14:01.930
I will give you tools
to start some goals.

01:14:01.930 --> 01:14:05.830
GILBERT: Senia received
a masters degree from
Martin Seligmans program

01:14:05.830 --> 01:14:07.900
at the University
of Pennsylvania.

01:14:07.900 --> 01:14:11.300
Shes trying to help Bill put his
unemployment in perspective.

01:14:11.300 --> 01:14:12.800
Because the problem is obvious.

01:14:12.800 --> 01:14:14.160
The guy doesnt have a job

01:14:14.160 --> 01:14:16.060
and he wants to figure
out what he's doing.

01:14:16.060 --> 01:14:17.460
"But that... okay,
he knows that."

01:14:17.460 --> 01:14:19.600
He's known that for
a couple of months.

