01:27:31.660 --> 01:27:37.800
with people that we love.

01:27:37.800 --> 01:27:38.900
The secret to happiness is

01:27:38.900 --> 01:27:41.300
that there is no
secret to happiness--

01:27:41.300 --> 01:27:43.500
"that its a choice that
you make minute by minute,"

01:27:43.500 --> 01:27:45.000
second by second.

01:27:45.000 --> 01:27:49.160
And you have to be willing to
take the sour with the sweet.

01:27:49.160 --> 01:27:55.430
"Is happiness an experience,
you know, that comes and goes?"

01:27:55.430 --> 01:27:57.700
Or is it a state
that you can live in

01:27:57.700 --> 01:27:59.230
for long periods of time?

01:27:59.230 --> 01:28:01.430
I don't... I dont know.

01:28:01.430 --> 01:28:03.860
Im just happy I have
my wife and my children

01:28:03.860 --> 01:28:07.300
and my many dogs and
birds and cats and...

01:28:07.300 --> 01:28:09.430
maybe if we could lose
a couple of those dogs.

01:28:09.430 --> 01:28:12.730
I think the secret to
happiness is being busy.

01:28:12.730 --> 01:28:14.460
"The secret to happiness is,"

01:28:14.460 --> 01:28:17.530
you dont have time
to think: Am I happy?

01:28:17.530 --> 01:28:20.460
Human companionship
is the greatest joy.

01:28:20.460 --> 01:28:24.300
"If I look at the times in my
life where Im most happy,"

01:28:24.300 --> 01:28:26.000
where Im enjoying
myself the most

01:28:26.000 --> 01:28:29.360
is when Im with my
friends or my family

01:28:29.360 --> 01:28:31.660
"and Im doing something
adventurous,"

01:28:31.660 --> 01:28:39.130
something kind of mildly
dangerous and laughing a lot.

01:28:39.130 --> 01:28:42.860
"GILBERT: So, is there
a secret to happiness?"

01:28:42.860 --> 01:28:46.200
"Well, yes, but it isn't
very much of a secret."

01:28:46.200 --> 01:28:49.230
Scientific research suggests
that a lot of things matter--

01:28:49.230 --> 01:28:52.930
"money, health, work-- but
that one thing matters a lot,"

01:28:52.930 --> 01:28:57.660
and that thing is
social relationships.

01:28:57.660 --> 01:29:00.530
Were one of the most social
animals on our planet.

01:29:00.530 --> 01:29:02.900
"We need each other for
just about everything,"

01:29:02.900 --> 01:29:05.530
so it isnt very surprising
that natures designed us

01:29:05.530 --> 01:29:08.560
to experience happiness when
we're connected to others.

01:29:08.560 --> 01:29:14.100
"Family, friends, lovers--"

01:29:14.100 --> 01:29:17.000
those are the social connections
that matter the most.

01:29:17.000 --> 01:29:19.260
"When theyre
strong, were happy."

01:29:19.260 --> 01:29:21.760
"When theyre lost,
were devastated."

01:29:21.760 --> 01:29:23.500
WOMAN: How are you?

01:29:23.500 --> 01:29:24.830
"STUDENT: Im good, how are you?"

01:29:24.830 --> 01:29:27.530
Hello...

01:29:27.530 --> 01:29:31.300
"GILBERT: Renee and Bryan Cloyd
live in Blacksburg, Virginia."

01:29:31.300 --> 01:29:34.400
Theyre doing today what they
do several times each year--

01:29:34.400 --> 01:29:37.930
driving a group of college
students over a hundred miles

01:29:37.930 --> 01:29:40.530
to rural Appalachia
to help repair homes

01:29:40.530 --> 01:29:45.530
in this impoverished community.

01:29:45.530 --> 01:29:47.260
You want to go head up this way?

01:29:47.260 --> 01:29:49.200
GILBERT: The Cloyds are
volunteering their time

01:29:49.200 --> 01:29:50.700
to help other people...

01:29:50.700 --> 01:29:52.860
"No, dont touch it
until you get one."

01:29:52.860 --> 01:29:55.030
"There you go, you just
snap the line, ladies."

01:29:55.030 --> 01:29:57.060
GILBERT: But theyre also
hoping to help themselves.

01:29:57.060 --> 01:30:00.330
RENEE CLOYD: Someone said
theres been a shooting
at Virginia Tech.

01:30:00.330 --> 01:30:02.530
"I didn't think about it,"

01:30:02.530 --> 01:30:06.000
and then something just hit.

01:30:06.000 --> 01:30:07.360
(siren wailing)

01:30:07.360 --> 01:30:08.800
"I turned on the
radio, just listening,"

01:30:08.800 --> 01:30:10.400
"trying to find some news,"

01:30:10.400 --> 01:30:15.060
and I heard that 22 had
been shot and killed

01:30:15.060 --> 01:30:18.200
at Virginia Tech.

01:30:18.200 --> 01:30:21.000
"I remember screaming,"

01:30:21.000 --> 01:30:24.230
and I called my mom cause
I knew she had a computer.

01:30:24.230 --> 01:30:26.730
"And I said, ""Could you please
check on the computer?"""

01:30:26.730 --> 01:30:31.560
"GILBERT: On April 16, 2007,
their daughter, Austin,"

01:30:31.560 --> 01:30:35.400
"a freshman at Virginia
Tech, was killed
in a shooting rampage"

01:30:35.400 --> 01:30:38.730
that left 33 people dead.

01:30:38.730 --> 01:30:41.400
BRYAN CLOYD: We were
trying to call Austin.

01:30:41.400 --> 01:30:43.260
Every other parent
and every other friend

01:30:43.260 --> 01:30:48.560
was trying to call
those students.

01:30:48.560 --> 01:30:52.760
And I heard from one of the
emergency response workers

01:30:52.760 --> 01:30:56.860
the most difficult thing
for them was to hear

01:30:56.860 --> 01:31:04.400
the cell phones going off
and being unable to answer.

01:31:04.400 --> 01:31:13.000
"But just hearing all
those cell phones going
off, over and over."

01:31:13.000 --> 01:31:16.100
That's what that day was like.

01:31:16.100 --> 01:31:23.860
It was a day of horror
and hopelessness.

01:31:23.860 --> 01:31:25.800
Sometimes its really
comforting to be in here.

01:31:25.800 --> 01:31:27.460
"I mean, this is a picture
of she and her friend."

01:31:27.460 --> 01:31:29.560
Had fun at football games.

01:31:29.560 --> 01:31:36.300
"BRYAN: You know, the initial
emotion when we lost Austin"

01:31:36.300 --> 01:31:39.530
was just like the life
had been sucked out of us.

01:31:39.530 --> 01:31:43.530
"And, um..."

01:31:43.530 --> 01:31:46.960
not only...

01:31:46.960 --> 01:31:51.260
we had no sense of direction...

01:31:51.260 --> 01:31:58.400
no sense of how we would
ever get past that moment.

01:31:58.400 --> 01:32:02.100
"GILBERT: The Cloyds kept asking
themselves, ""What next?"""

01:32:02.100 --> 01:32:05.260
"But try as they might, they
just couldn't find an answer."

01:32:05.260 --> 01:32:06.960
BRYAN: Life can end

01:32:06.960 --> 01:32:11.560
"so quickly that everything one
does, everything one plans for,"

01:32:11.560 --> 01:32:14.860
"dreams of, can be
gone in an instant."

01:32:14.860 --> 01:32:17.560
"So, what's life about?"

01:32:17.560 --> 01:32:22.130
"RENEE: I thought, ""Okay,
we gotta let people
know who Austin is."

01:32:22.130 --> 01:32:24.130
"""Shes not just a dead person,"

01:32:24.130 --> 01:32:27.700
"she was a vital person who
was making an impact."""

01:32:27.700 --> 01:32:29.460
"GILBERT: As a high
school student,"

01:32:29.460 --> 01:32:32.760
Austin did volunteer
work in Appalachia.

01:32:32.760 --> 01:32:34.530
Her parents hoped that
by devoting themselves

01:32:34.530 --> 01:32:36.300
"to her cause,"

01:32:36.300 --> 01:32:37.500
theyd connect with the people

01:32:37.500 --> 01:32:39.300
whod connected
with their daughter

01:32:39.300 --> 01:32:41.600
and move their
own lives forward.

01:32:41.600 --> 01:32:44.260
BRYAN: Most of the people
that we meet out here

01:32:44.260 --> 01:32:48.700
"that we work with on their
homes, they all have a story."

01:32:48.700 --> 01:32:54.700
"And the story almost
always involves tragedy,"

01:32:54.700 --> 01:32:57.130
something thats happened
to their family.

01:32:57.130 --> 01:32:59.030
RENEE: Thank you very much for
letting us visit with you.

01:32:59.030 --> 01:33:00.530
WOMAN: Thank you for doing it.

01:33:00.530 --> 01:33:04.930
BRYAN: And it causes me
to know everyone has pain.

01:33:04.930 --> 01:33:10.430
So it helps to put our
grief in perspective.

01:33:10.430 --> 01:33:14.400
"RENEE: Austins
favorite quote was,"

01:33:14.400 --> 01:33:16.730
"""No one can do everything,"

01:33:16.730 --> 01:33:19.260
"""but everyone
can do something, and if
everyone does something,"

01:33:19.260 --> 01:33:22.360
"then together we can
change the world."""

01:33:22.360 --> 01:33:24.660
"Hey, ladies, hows it going?"

01:33:24.660 --> 01:33:26.660
BRYAN: I dont know
how long it takes

01:33:26.660 --> 01:33:32.760
for people to reflect
upon memories of children

01:33:32.760 --> 01:33:43.030
that theyve lost and feel
mostly happy about that memory

01:33:43.030 --> 01:33:45.260
instead of mostly sad.

01:33:45.260 --> 01:33:50.200
"For me now, it's still mostly
sad, and maybe a little happy."

01:33:50.200 --> 01:33:51.530
"Okay, why dont yall help him"

01:33:51.530 --> 01:33:53.000
so he doesnt cut
his fingers off.

01:33:53.000 --> 01:33:54.960
Stress safety to this man.

01:33:54.960 --> 01:33:58.160
RENEE: A lot of people
in this world just dont
have the confidence

01:33:58.160 --> 01:34:00.260
of being loved.

01:34:00.260 --> 01:34:03.100
And I personally
feel like I have that

01:34:03.100 --> 01:34:05.030
to be able to give to others.

01:34:05.030 --> 01:34:06.960
"So, coming on trips like this"

01:34:06.960 --> 01:34:08.330
"and getting to know
these students,"

01:34:08.330 --> 01:34:11.360
"I cant do it for
Austin anymore,"

01:34:11.360 --> 01:34:14.830
"but if I can just give
it to one more person,"

01:34:14.830 --> 01:34:19.660
then maybe they can give
it to someone else...

01:34:19.660 --> 01:34:23.830
"um, because I don't have
her to give it to anymore."

01:34:23.830 --> 01:34:26.160
"Youre right, Jared."

01:34:26.160 --> 01:34:28.660
"Yeah, okay."

01:34:28.660 --> 01:34:32.300
GILBERT: Can we really
transmit happiness to others?

01:34:32.300 --> 01:34:34.900
"If we do something to make
another person happy,"

01:34:34.900 --> 01:34:36.900
do they then do the same
thing for somebody else?

01:34:36.900 --> 01:34:40.830
"In fact, new evidence suggests
that happiness may be"

01:34:40.830 --> 01:34:43.000
"as contagious as
the common cold,"

01:34:43.000 --> 01:34:45.800
that it can be passed
along from person to person

01:34:45.800 --> 01:34:53.900
and that it can travel farther
and faster than anyone imagined.

01:34:53.900 --> 01:34:58.700
"This is Framingham,
Massachusetts."

01:34:58.700 --> 01:35:02.400
"In 1948, medical researchers
began tracking the residents"

01:35:02.400 --> 01:35:05.000
of this town trying to
learn about the behaviors

01:35:05.000 --> 01:35:08.900
that cause heart disease.

01:35:08.900 --> 01:35:11.630
Their work continues today.

01:35:11.630 --> 01:35:13.060
"Known as the
Framingham Heart Study,"

01:35:13.060 --> 01:35:15.300
its one of the
worlds most extensive

01:35:15.300 --> 01:35:16.560
"epidemiological studies,"

01:35:16.560 --> 01:35:19.030
containing six
decades worth of data

01:35:19.030 --> 01:35:22.230
"on the health of more
than 15,000 people."

01:35:22.230 --> 01:35:25.000
And hidden in this
mountain of data

01:35:25.000 --> 01:35:27.660
is a deep and powerful secret

01:35:27.660 --> 01:35:30.630
about the nature
of human happiness.

01:35:30.630 --> 01:35:34.160
NICHOLAS CHRISTAKIS:
Your happiness depends

01:35:34.160 --> 01:35:37.160
upon whole large clusters of
people you dont even know

01:35:37.160 --> 01:35:39.130
and who you have
no way of knowing.

01:35:39.130 --> 01:35:43.960
GILBERT: Nicholas Christakis is
a physician and a sociologist.

01:35:43.960 --> 01:35:46.100
He became interested
in the Framingham study

01:35:46.100 --> 01:35:48.360
"not because he was
interested in heart disease,"

01:35:48.360 --> 01:35:50.900
but because he was interested
in social connections.

01:35:50.900 --> 01:35:52.300
CHRISTAKIS: These individuals

01:35:52.300 --> 01:35:55.500
had had their social network
ties repeatedly assessed

01:35:55.500 --> 01:35:57.500
over this 32-year period

01:35:57.500 --> 01:35:59.430
"and, as it turns out,
had had various aspects"

01:35:59.430 --> 01:36:01.630
of their emotional
lives assessed as well.

01:36:01.630 --> 01:36:03.030
So what we could tell is

01:36:03.030 --> 01:36:05.500
we could tell who these
people were connected to

01:36:05.500 --> 01:36:07.700
every four years
or so for 30 years

01:36:07.700 --> 01:36:09.400
"and we could
tell, for example,"

01:36:09.400 --> 01:36:12.100
whether they were happy
or depressed or lonely

01:36:12.100 --> 01:36:15.530
"and, in some cases, anxious,
repeatedly across time."

01:36:15.530 --> 01:36:17.760
"GILBERT: Using the
Framingham data,"

01:36:17.760 --> 01:36:20.630
Christakis and his
colleagues mapped out a web

01:36:20.630 --> 01:36:22.630
"of more than
50,000 connections"

01:36:22.630 --> 01:36:24.860
"between friends,
family and co-workers"

01:36:24.860 --> 01:36:27.260
who participated in the study.

01:36:27.260 --> 01:36:30.600
Then they began to calculate
how changes in the happiness

01:36:30.600 --> 01:36:33.700
of any single person affected
the happiness of others

01:36:33.700 --> 01:36:36.030
in this vast web
of relationships.

01:36:36.030 --> 01:36:38.330
The results were astounding.

01:36:38.330 --> 01:36:42.630
"CHRISTAKIS: What we
found is that if your
friend becomes happy,"

01:36:42.630 --> 01:36:44.660
it increases the probability
that you will become happy

01:36:44.660 --> 01:36:46.600
by about 15%.

01:36:46.600 --> 01:36:48.430
And if your friends
friend becomes happy--

01:36:48.430 --> 01:36:49.800
"someone you dont
even know, perhaps--"

01:36:49.800 --> 01:36:51.260
it increases the probability

01:36:51.260 --> 01:36:53.200
that youll become
happy by about 10%.

01:36:53.200 --> 01:36:56.560
"Its only when we get to
four degrees of separation,"

01:36:56.560 --> 01:36:58.060
only when were speaking

01:36:58.060 --> 01:37:01.130
"of your friends
friends friends friend,"

01:37:01.130 --> 01:37:03.930
that that persons emotional
state is no longer associated

01:37:03.930 --> 01:37:05.460
with your emotional state.

01:37:05.460 --> 01:37:09.230
"GILBERT: Everyone
knows that people can
make each other happy,"

01:37:09.230 --> 01:37:12.930
"but before this study,
no one had any idea"

01:37:12.930 --> 01:37:16.200
just how powerful
this effect could be.

01:37:16.200 --> 01:37:18.030
Christakiss work shows
that happiness spreads

01:37:18.030 --> 01:37:20.960
through social
networks like a virus;

01:37:20.960 --> 01:37:25.630
"that happiness is, in a very
real sense, contagious."

01:37:25.630 --> 01:37:28.760
Theres no doubt about
it: were all connected.

01:37:28.760 --> 01:37:30.960
And those connections
exert a powerful influence

01:37:30.960 --> 01:37:32.560
on our happiness.

01:37:32.560 --> 01:37:37.260
Sometimes they can
even save our lives.

01:37:37.260 --> 01:37:40.400
"MICHAEL MADDAUS: I
lived here about 40 years
ago, when I was a kid."

01:37:40.400 --> 01:37:46.630
"Just walking in the door of my
house was so, so unpleasant."

01:37:46.630 --> 01:37:50.200
"GILBERT: Michael Maddaus was
born in Minneapolis, Minnesota,"

01:37:50.200 --> 01:37:52.530
and the troubled relationships
of his childhood

01:37:52.530 --> 01:37:54.260
left an indelible mark.

01:37:54.260 --> 01:37:59.200
MADDAUS: I was an only child.

01:37:59.200 --> 01:38:01.130
I grew up with my mother
and my grandmother.

01:38:01.130 --> 01:38:05.230
My mother worked two jobs
as a waitress to support us

01:38:05.230 --> 01:38:10.500
because my grandmother was home
all the time taking care of me.

01:38:10.500 --> 01:38:11.960
The lid came off

01:38:11.960 --> 01:38:13.960
that predictable
situation by two events:

01:38:13.960 --> 01:38:16.460
"my grandmother died,
which left us in a void,"

01:38:16.460 --> 01:38:21.300
and then my stepfather came in.

01:38:21.300 --> 01:38:36.160
And that's when the
alcoholism reared its head.

01:38:36.160 --> 01:38:38.830
My mother would be in bed.

01:38:38.830 --> 01:38:42.530
My stepfather would be up in a
chair with cocktail in hand.

01:38:42.530 --> 01:38:45.930
"My mother would be bedridden
for maybe up to a month,"

01:38:45.930 --> 01:38:50.300
and she would even call
for me in a drunken tone

01:38:50.300 --> 01:38:53.330
"to bring her a drink, or
food, or something like that."

01:38:53.330 --> 01:38:56.060
"I was, of course,
bitter and angry"

01:38:56.060 --> 01:38:58.400
about what was now going on.

01:38:58.400 --> 01:39:01.560
"In essence Id lost my mother,
the mother that I had known,"

01:39:01.560 --> 01:39:05.300
to this alcoholic life.

01:39:05.300 --> 01:39:09.300
And thats when I
began to really start

01:39:09.300 --> 01:39:12.800
living more on the streets...

01:39:12.800 --> 01:39:17.400
"and started to get into trouble
with my friends, my new family."

01:39:17.400 --> 01:39:20.160
"And the trouble started
simply with shoplifting,"

01:39:20.160 --> 01:39:23.730
"escalated to
burglaries, car thefts,"

01:39:23.730 --> 01:39:25.630
so that we were pretty
much running around

01:39:25.630 --> 01:39:27.600
doing what we wanted.

01:39:27.600 --> 01:39:30.460
Right over here was my friends
house and he used to deal LSD

01:39:30.460 --> 01:39:32.500
right out of the back
of the house there.

01:39:32.500 --> 01:39:34.930
A good source for all
of us at the time.

01:39:34.930 --> 01:39:38.000
"I and my friends, wed just
do everything in our power"

01:39:38.000 --> 01:39:41.100
to find ways to alter our mood.

01:39:41.100 --> 01:39:45.560
"We... you know, drinking,
drugs, LSD, speed, you name it."

01:39:45.560 --> 01:39:49.860
It was pretty much anything
we could get our hands on.

01:39:49.860 --> 01:39:51.730
Right up here on
the left is a house

01:39:51.730 --> 01:39:54.930
that we were all holed up in
and we were busted up there

01:39:54.930 --> 01:39:58.400
by a very spectacular
bunch of police outside.

01:39:58.400 --> 01:40:02.100
"And they had us right over
here, in front of this house,"

01:40:02.100 --> 01:40:07.500
"all of us pinned down,
handcuffed on the ground."

01:40:07.500 --> 01:40:09.930
I was arrested 24 times total.

01:40:09.930 --> 01:40:12.030
"The vast majority of
that was for car theft,"

01:40:12.030 --> 01:40:14.700
occasional break-ins

01:40:14.700 --> 01:40:18.360
"and other sorts of
misdemeanors, drunken behavior,"

01:40:18.360 --> 01:40:21.200
disorderly stuff and the like.

01:40:21.200 --> 01:40:23.260
But I remember every
time going down

01:40:23.260 --> 01:40:26.130
to the juvenile detention center
with its drab green cement walls

01:40:26.130 --> 01:40:29.400
and just a profound
sense of depression

01:40:29.400 --> 01:40:32.800
that would occur within me
and just the hopelessness.

01:40:32.800 --> 01:40:36.160
And to this day I can remember

01:40:36.160 --> 01:40:38.760
"the deep, gut-wrenching
depression"

01:40:38.760 --> 01:40:40.760
that would come
over me in a wave.

01:40:40.760 --> 01:40:48.130
"You know, I don't know
what the future holds."

01:40:48.130 --> 01:40:50.660
I had a meeting with
my parole officer

01:40:50.660 --> 01:40:53.860
after Id been arrested one
more time subsequently.

01:40:53.860 --> 01:40:57.100
"And I was sitting in the car,
outside the high school,"

01:40:57.100 --> 01:40:59.630
"and he told me, ""You're done."

01:40:59.630 --> 01:41:02.460
"One more arrest and
you're going to be
tried as an adult."""

01:41:02.460 --> 01:41:05.730
I had at least the
insight to know

01:41:05.730 --> 01:41:07.930
"that if I stayed in
this environment,"

01:41:07.930 --> 01:41:10.330
I was gonna get
in trouble again.

01:41:10.330 --> 01:41:12.860
"GILBERT: Although many
of his friends would
soon be in prison,"

01:41:12.860 --> 01:41:15.530
"fate had something different
in mind for Maddaus,"

01:41:15.530 --> 01:41:18.960
whose life was changed forever
by a single social connection.

01:41:18.960 --> 01:41:21.400
I got a job at a very
high-end furniture store

01:41:21.400 --> 01:41:25.000
that sold very expensive
modern furniture.

01:41:25.000 --> 01:41:29.900
Its an environment that
allowed me to learn a lot

01:41:29.900 --> 01:41:32.060
"about the other side of life,"

01:41:32.060 --> 01:41:35.600
"where there was money, culture,
art, wine and the like,"

01:41:35.600 --> 01:41:37.700
and this was something I
had not experienced before.

01:41:37.700 --> 01:41:40.400
So it allowed me to become
aware of this as a possibility.

01:41:40.400 --> 01:41:45.860
But the real transition for me
in terms of helping to guide me

01:41:45.860 --> 01:41:48.300
came through a fluke
interaction that I had

01:41:48.300 --> 01:41:51.000
in delivering
furniture to a surgeon.

01:41:51.000 --> 01:41:53.400
"It was a very big
job that we had,"

01:41:53.400 --> 01:41:55.500
and I ended up going
out there multiple times

01:41:55.500 --> 01:41:58.100
to install custom-made
furniture.

01:41:58.100 --> 01:42:00.600
And so I got to know him.

01:42:00.600 --> 01:42:03.500
"For whatever reason,
he saw something in me"

01:42:03.500 --> 01:42:07.960
and he decided to take
me under his wing.

01:42:07.960 --> 01:42:13.500
"STACY ROBACK: My first
impressions of Mike, when
he first came in the door,"

01:42:13.500 --> 01:42:20.330
there was a spark there that
was blatantly obvious to me.

01:42:20.330 --> 01:42:25.900
And his persistence in
pursuing our relationship

01:42:25.900 --> 01:42:30.900
was conspicuous and
it was infectious.

01:42:30.900 --> 01:42:33.230
I wrote a letter to the
dean of the medical school.

01:42:33.230 --> 01:42:34.860
"I mean, it makes
no sense. Right."

01:42:34.860 --> 01:42:36.230
I wouldnt do it today.

01:42:36.230 --> 01:42:38.300
MADDAUS: I would go out
to his house on Saturdays

01:42:38.300 --> 01:42:40.460
and just hang out with him.

01:42:40.460 --> 01:42:42.400
And he might take
a nap on the couch

01:42:42.400 --> 01:42:44.930
while I would sit there and
watch football or something.

01:42:44.930 --> 01:42:47.600
But when it came time for
me to ask him questions

01:42:47.600 --> 01:42:50.860
"and get some guidance,
he always gave
me the right advice."

01:42:50.860 --> 01:42:52.530
"He said, ""I had
a difficult time"

01:42:52.530 --> 01:42:55.230
"""even getting a
high school diploma,"

01:42:55.230 --> 01:42:57.860
"""and I havent been to
college, and I cant read,"

01:42:57.860 --> 01:43:00.500
"and I can't add a column
of numbers together."""

01:43:00.500 --> 01:43:07.160
"And my response to that was,
""Well, just... just do it."""

01:43:07.160 --> 01:43:11.360
"MADDAUS: He saw worth in me,
and it could be developed."

01:43:11.360 --> 01:43:17.060
And that was what
decided my fate.

01:43:17.060 --> 01:43:19.160
Im a full professor
of thoracic surgery

01:43:19.160 --> 01:43:24.130
in the department of surgery at
the University of Minnesota.

01:43:24.130 --> 01:43:25.900
And I landed upon surgery

01:43:25.900 --> 01:43:28.100
when I got onto the rotation
as a medical student.

01:43:28.100 --> 01:43:31.700
"All of a sudden, here we are in
a high-adrenaline environment,"

01:43:31.700 --> 01:43:35.730
"risky activity,
life and death--"

01:43:35.730 --> 01:43:39.600
all the things that were
certainly embedded in me

01:43:39.600 --> 01:43:41.700
and my past and how I grew up.

01:43:41.700 --> 01:43:43.800
I fit in just perfectly.

01:43:43.800 --> 01:43:48.460
ANN MASTEN: The story of Mikes
life illustrates beautifully

01:43:48.460 --> 01:43:50.460
what happens in childhood

01:43:50.460 --> 01:43:54.000
and going down a dark
road doesn't doom you.

01:43:54.000 --> 01:43:56.860
That you can turn
your life around

01:43:56.860 --> 01:44:03.030
and you can construct a new life
with the help of other people.

01:44:03.030 --> 01:44:04.660
GILBERT: Psychologist Ann Masten

01:44:04.660 --> 01:44:07.560
studies how children
respond to adversity.

01:44:07.560 --> 01:44:10.260
She became interested in Maddaus
because of the way he used

01:44:10.260 --> 01:44:14.500
his adult relationships to
overcome a troubled youth.

01:44:14.500 --> 01:44:18.360
He encountered people who
began to care about him.

01:44:18.360 --> 01:44:21.830
He connected with mentors
who opened doors for him

01:44:21.830 --> 01:44:22.930
and coached him.

01:44:22.930 --> 01:44:27.000
"Yeah, we probably
should check..."

01:44:27.000 --> 01:44:30.460
"GILBERT: For almost 30
years, Masten has been
working on a study"

01:44:30.460 --> 01:44:32.530
"that tracks over 200 people,"

01:44:32.530 --> 01:44:37.600
"many of whom,
like Maddaus, grew up in
difficult circumstances."

01:44:37.600 --> 01:44:41.230
"MASTEN: We recruited
them when they were
eight to 12 years old,"

01:44:41.230 --> 01:44:43.600
"and then we followed them
up after about seven years,"

01:44:43.600 --> 01:44:45.200
ten years and then 20 years.

01:44:45.200 --> 01:44:49.260
We wanted to study
what was happening

01:44:49.260 --> 01:44:50.730
both when things were going well

01:44:50.730 --> 01:44:52.400
and when things were
not going so well.

01:44:52.400 --> 01:44:57.330
And we learned a lot
about the nature of stress

01:44:57.330 --> 01:44:59.330
that kids encounter

01:44:59.330 --> 01:45:02.260
and also about all the
kinds of protective factors

01:45:02.260 --> 01:45:04.660
that seem to make a difference
in children's lives.

01:45:04.660 --> 01:45:06.630
GILBERT: Mastens
findings tell us

01:45:06.630 --> 01:45:09.530
that the key to overcoming
childhood adversity

01:45:09.530 --> 01:45:12.230
lies in developing
strong relationships

01:45:12.230 --> 01:45:14.730
"with competent and
caring individuals,"

01:45:14.730 --> 01:45:17.400
regardless of how or
when we meet them.

01:45:17.400 --> 01:45:19.530
"MASTEN: When you're young,
they're parenting-type figures."

01:45:19.530 --> 01:45:20.900
"When youre older,"

01:45:20.900 --> 01:45:23.430
"they can be mentors,
friends, romantic partners."

01:45:23.430 --> 01:45:25.100
Any concerns or issues?

01:45:25.100 --> 01:45:26.300
You got any pains?

01:45:26.300 --> 01:45:27.660
"MASTEN: In Mikes case,"

01:45:27.660 --> 01:45:30.360
"these kind of people
came into his life late,"

01:45:30.360 --> 01:45:32.900
when he was at the
doorstep of adulthood.

01:45:32.900 --> 01:45:37.360
"And he was optimistic, even
though he probably didnt have"

01:45:37.360 --> 01:45:40.230
too many reasons
to be optimistic.

01:45:40.230 --> 01:45:42.800
"And I think people around
him responded to that,"

01:45:42.800 --> 01:45:47.000
to his motivation and interest
in going in a new direction.

01:45:47.000 --> 01:45:49.730
And I think what
you see in his life

01:45:49.730 --> 01:45:55.760
is a kind of positive snowball.

01:45:55.760 --> 01:45:57.860
"MADDAUS: When I reflect back
about, how did this happen?"

01:45:57.860 --> 01:46:01.960
How did I manage to make a
success out of this mess?

01:46:01.960 --> 01:46:05.430
I go back to the... the
observation of others

01:46:05.430 --> 01:46:09.460
and using those as
significant opportunities

01:46:09.460 --> 01:46:10.800
for personal development.

01:46:10.800 --> 01:46:13.460
(piano melody playing)

01:46:13.460 --> 01:46:14.960
"Without a doubt,"

01:46:14.960 --> 01:46:18.060
one of the most important
things that bring me happiness

01:46:18.060 --> 01:46:21.800
"is being engaged in my family,
in taking care of them,"

01:46:21.800 --> 01:46:24.500
"in fostering my
childrens development,"

01:46:24.500 --> 01:46:26.600
in being a good
husband to my wife.

01:46:26.600 --> 01:46:29.900
"These are sometimes trite
comments that people make,"

01:46:29.900 --> 01:46:31.560
"you know, being
a good husband,"

01:46:31.560 --> 01:46:33.060
"being a father and
all that stuff,"

01:46:33.060 --> 01:46:35.560
but I actually mean it and its
something I came to learn.

01:46:35.560 --> 01:46:37.800
It wasn't something
that was just immediate.

01:46:37.800 --> 01:46:42.700
"For me, happiness
means being engaged"

01:46:42.700 --> 01:46:47.060
in things that
involve other people

01:46:47.060 --> 01:46:55.530
and being committed to something
that is about other people.

01:46:55.530 --> 01:46:59.030
GILBERT: Social connections are
clearly the key to happiness.

01:46:59.030 --> 01:47:02.630
"That's a cause for
celebration, but it's
also a cause for worry,"

01:47:02.630 --> 01:47:04.460
"because as people age,"

01:47:04.460 --> 01:47:07.800
"their social networks
get smaller and smaller,"

01:47:07.800 --> 01:47:09.360
"which suggests that
the older we get,"

01:47:09.360 --> 01:47:11.000
the unhappier we should become.

01:47:11.000 --> 01:47:13.560
"And yet, surprising
new evidence reveals"

01:47:13.560 --> 01:47:16.000
its usually the
other way around.

01:47:16.000 --> 01:47:19.860
"As we get older, were
increasingly clear"

01:47:19.860 --> 01:47:22.730
"about what our strengths are,
what our weaknesses are."

01:47:22.730 --> 01:47:26.230
Were increasingly clear
about who cares about us

01:47:26.230 --> 01:47:27.700
"and who doesn't,"

01:47:27.700 --> 01:47:30.030
and so we're able to
mold our worlds better.

01:47:30.030 --> 01:47:34.660
"GILBERT: Over the last
two decades, psychologist
Laura Carstensen"

01:47:34.660 --> 01:47:36.660
has been monitoring
hundreds of individuals

01:47:36.660 --> 01:47:39.900
to see how their emotional
lives change as they age.

01:47:39.900 --> 01:47:41.400
CARSTENSEN: We recruited

01:47:41.400 --> 01:47:47.000
"a group of participants who
were initially aged 18 to 94,"

01:47:47.000 --> 01:47:51.030
and we asked them to carry an
electronic pager with them.

01:47:51.030 --> 01:47:55.430
"Each time they were paged,
we asked them to tell us"

01:47:55.430 --> 01:47:57.700
the extent to which
they were feeling

01:47:57.700 --> 01:48:00.560
each of 19 different emotions.

01:48:00.560 --> 01:48:02.560
And we had them give
us this information

01:48:02.560 --> 01:48:06.600
35 times during a week.

01:48:06.600 --> 01:48:09.260
GILBERT: Carstensens findings
tell us that people become

01:48:09.260 --> 01:48:11.600
"increasingly positive
as they grow older,"

01:48:11.600 --> 01:48:13.500
as long as they arent suffering

01:48:13.500 --> 01:48:15.930
from physical pain or
debilitating illness.

01:48:15.930 --> 01:48:17.600
CARSTENSEN: It was
pretty dramatic.

01:48:17.600 --> 01:48:21.030
"Essentially, what we
found is that 70-year-olds"

01:48:21.030 --> 01:48:23.900
were experiencing
fewer negative emotions

01:48:23.900 --> 01:48:25.260
than 40-year-olds;

01:48:25.260 --> 01:48:27.130
40-year-olds were experiencing
fewer negative emotions

01:48:27.130 --> 01:48:28.830
than 20-year-olds.

01:48:28.830 --> 01:48:33.060
"GILBERT: In
later studies, Carstensen
identified several causes"

01:48:33.060 --> 01:48:35.130
for this remarkable shift.

01:48:35.130 --> 01:48:36.560
CARSTENSEN: Humans know
that they're mortal.

01:48:36.560 --> 01:48:40.530
We know that we have only
a certain amount of time

01:48:40.530 --> 01:48:42.530
"on this planet,"

01:48:42.530 --> 01:48:46.200
and this changes
peoples motivation

01:48:46.200 --> 01:48:49.160
and changes their
emotional experience.

01:48:49.160 --> 01:48:53.330
"As we age, it appears
that people are better"

01:48:53.330 --> 01:48:55.300
"at experiencing the moment,"

01:48:55.300 --> 01:48:59.060
enjoying what theyre doing at
a particular point in time.

01:48:59.060 --> 01:49:03.960
"In some sense, it's the
silver lining of getting old"

01:49:03.960 --> 01:49:07.130
that we don't have to
prepare for the future.

01:49:07.130 --> 01:49:09.300
We don't have the
burden of the future.

01:49:09.300 --> 01:49:12.260
GILBERT: The major
consequence of this change?

01:49:12.260 --> 01:49:15.600
Older people tend to alter
their social behavior.

01:49:15.600 --> 01:49:17.130
CARSTENSEN: When
motivation shifts

01:49:17.130 --> 01:49:19.360
"so youre focusing on what
matters most in life,"

01:49:19.360 --> 01:49:22.100
for most people they start to
focus on their relationships

01:49:22.100 --> 01:49:24.830
and their closest relationships.

01:49:24.830 --> 01:49:26.500
You value your friendships.

01:49:26.500 --> 01:49:29.830
"You value your
children, your family."

01:49:29.830 --> 01:49:32.960
GILBERT: Betty Schneider
is 87 years old.

01:49:32.960 --> 01:49:36.460
Shes one of hundreds of elderly
people who have participated

01:49:36.460 --> 01:49:37.960
in Carstensens studies.

01:49:37.960 --> 01:49:40.130
"SCHNEIDER: As
Ive become older,"

01:49:40.130 --> 01:49:43.730
it seems that I really
appreciate my life even more.

01:49:43.730 --> 01:49:48.100
"When I was younger, I didn't
even think about old age."

01:49:48.100 --> 01:49:54.460
But it turned out
to be wonderful.

01:49:54.460 --> 01:49:56.660
GILBERT: Betty is a widow.

01:49:56.660 --> 01:50:00.500
"Her husband, Jack, succumbed
to a stroke six years ago."

01:50:00.500 --> 01:50:03.200
"But like many people
in her situation,"

01:50:03.200 --> 01:50:04.800
she doesnt dwell on the loss.

01:50:04.800 --> 01:50:08.660
"In fact, her daily life
is remarkably busy."

01:50:08.660 --> 01:50:12.660
"She takes classes, spends
time with her grandchildren"

01:50:12.660 --> 01:50:15.200
and has a full social schedule.

01:50:15.200 --> 01:50:17.660
SCHNEIDER: I miss Jack.

01:50:17.660 --> 01:50:19.660
We did so many things together.

01:50:19.660 --> 01:50:22.760
We were married for 61 years.

01:50:22.760 --> 01:50:29.360
"And after Jack passed on,
it was... pretty glum,"

01:50:29.360 --> 01:50:31.760
and gradually it's
become better again.

01:50:31.760 --> 01:50:33.430
"Theres lots going on,"

01:50:33.430 --> 01:50:38.400
"and he would enjoy a lot of the
things that Im doing, um..."

01:50:38.400 --> 01:50:40.630
"but Im sorry hes not here,"

01:50:40.630 --> 01:50:46.660
but Im just so glad we
had all those years.

01:50:46.660 --> 01:50:48.360
CARSTENSEN: In some
ways it challenges

01:50:48.360 --> 01:50:51.900
"our most fundamental
assumptions about happiness,"

01:50:51.900 --> 01:50:57.460
because we think that happiness
is derived from youth

01:50:57.460 --> 01:51:01.260
"and power and
attractiveness, health,"

01:51:01.260 --> 01:51:03.930
"all of these things
that decline with age,"

01:51:03.930 --> 01:51:07.730
but yet were finding
that among older people

01:51:07.730 --> 01:51:11.730
"who are clearly suffering
these kinds of losses,"

01:51:11.730 --> 01:51:15.300
are also somehow experiencing
life emotionally

01:51:15.300 --> 01:51:17.960
better than ever.

01:51:17.960 --> 01:51:20.730
SCHNEIDER: I feel
very fortunate.

01:51:20.730 --> 01:51:24.100
I often go through all the good
things that have happened--

01:51:24.100 --> 01:51:27.360
what's been good today.

01:51:27.360 --> 01:51:29.600
Its interesting younger
people dont really believe

01:51:29.600 --> 01:51:33.530
that you can be optimistic
and feel positive

01:51:33.530 --> 01:51:36.700
"about things that are
happening when youre old,"

01:51:36.700 --> 01:51:39.560
"but believe me, you do."

01:51:39.560 --> 01:51:43.230
"And I know I dont have
a long time to live,"

01:51:43.230 --> 01:51:52.830
"but its... its turned out to be
a very, very rewarding time."

01:51:52.830 --> 01:51:54.860
"GILBERT: We start
out in high chairs,"

01:51:54.860 --> 01:51:57.360
"we end up in wheelchairs,"

01:51:57.360 --> 01:52:00.960
"and somewhere between the two,
we all have to figure out"

01:52:00.960 --> 01:52:02.130
where our happiness lies

01:52:02.130 --> 01:52:05.560
and then start marching
in that direction.

01:52:05.560 --> 01:52:09.160
So who brought the map?

01:52:09.160 --> 01:52:10.560
"Well, everyone did."

01:52:10.560 --> 01:52:14.800
"Grandmothers and
uncles, priests and
rabbis, taxi drivers,"

01:52:14.800 --> 01:52:16.800
"bartenders,
motivational speakers--"

01:52:16.800 --> 01:52:19.460
"they all have something
to say about happiness,"

01:52:19.460 --> 01:52:21.930
but they don't all
say the same thing.

01:52:21.930 --> 01:52:25.260
And that's where
science comes in.

01:52:25.260 --> 01:52:26.530
By using scientific methods

01:52:26.530 --> 01:52:29.900
"to identify the causes
of human happiness,"

01:52:29.900 --> 01:52:32.000
were learning that the
secret of happiness

01:52:32.000 --> 01:52:33.800
was never very secret.

01:52:33.800 --> 01:52:38.160
"Were connected to each other,
we belong to each other,"

01:52:38.160 --> 01:52:40.700
were made for each other.

01:52:40.700 --> 01:52:44.900
"Life is a journey through time,
and happiness is what happens"

01:52:44.900 --> 00:00:03.730
when we make that
journey together.